@node editorsdesk "From The Editor's Desk"
@toc contents
=============================================================================
@{b}From The Editor's Desk@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

Warm greetings during this cold season, I hope that you are sitting nice and
warm in front of your Amiga. The Amiga PSU is a great foot warmer if it is
sitting on the floor, by the way. Thank you for downloading issue 3.15 of 
WhatIFF?, this will mark almost four years of the magazine, while the 
frequency of issues has decreased from monthly to every four months, the 
number of contributors has increased and along with them the quality and 
content have improved as well.

So,to begin with I wish to thank everyone who has worked on the magazine in
2024: Andy Vaisey, Ivan Sorensen, John Scolieri, Kevin Saunders, Kristian 
Hesketh, Marytn Bampton, Roald Strauss, Rob O'Malley and Steve Lord. With
out their contributions the magazine would not have grown into what it has
become. 

In this issue we have a lot of hardware reviews for a variety of Amiga models
such as the RastPort and the A600GS. There are a few guides and I highly 
recommend having a read of the Blitz Basic Basics by Andy Vaisey. We are 
living in dire times with wars aplenty and nuclear war seemingly closer each
day. But the Amiga scene has thrived in 2024 with numerous new games and 
hardware releases. Like a fine wine, the Amiga is getting better and better
with age.

Before I go though I would like to mention that we now also have WhatIFF?
stickers and t-shirts available. These are not made for profit but as a fun
way to show support for the magazine. In addition the WhatIFF? forum has 
been updated to a better forum software, there were a few teething problems 
but thanks to Martyn, it is now fully functional with working e-mail 
notifications. I hope to see you around there. In addition content will be
uploaded that will not be available in the Amiga Guide version of the 
magazine. Finally the logo has been updated to something a bit more 
professional looking and the images have been reduced from 256 to 64
colours to reduce the loading times on slower Amigas.

Well, that covers everything, enjoy the magazine and thank again for
downloading and reading WhatIFF? Amiga Guide Magazine. See you again in 
2025!

@endnode

