@node shelltalk "Free For All About Anything"
@toc contents
=============================================================================
@{b}Shell Talk@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

We are at the end of another year, and much has happened around the world
and in the Amiga scene. While my morning newspaper has become a bit of a
depressing read I am always happy to concentrate on what the Amiga scene is
offering and this year has been a great one. I am in particular impressed by
how Amiga community in particular. Point in case, I recently decided to 
reduce most of my Amiga stuff, by this time I only had an A1200 and V4 
Standalone. 

Living in Japan space can be quite limited and in our home which is called a
'Danchi' which generally means government flat there is only one room where 
I can put my Amiga. But it is a small room and the A1200 takes up a lot 
space. It made me feel bad for my wife who does not have any space to do her 
stuff on the desk. So, I thought, well I have a V4 Standalone and that has 
been working very nicely, maybe I do not need the A1200 anymore. So, I 
decided to sell the A1200 off, well ... things were going well for a while 
until they didn't and one of the issues of the V4SA is that when things go 
bad, they really go bad. I started to get random issues with software that 
refused to work,even though they would load without issue the previous day.
This was software such as OctaMED and even simple programs likeProtext. 

While I think the V4SA is a fantastic machine it still has issues that make 
it a difficult replacement Amiga, especially if it is your only Amiga. After 
about two weeks of this I had to accept that I had 'flamingoed' up (Double 
points if you get that reference ;), with all the power that the V4SA 
offered, it still could not run software that is important to me,  stably 
or even at all.

What could I do?

Buying an A1200 has become prohibitively expensive, so I decided to try my
luck on Amibay and see if someone would be willing to 'swap' my V4SA for an 
A1200. I got a quick response from an Amibayer in the States and we got 
talking. I was still thinking about the swap when he offered to change the 
original white case for an A1200.net translucent case and throw in a TF1230. 

Well,I could not resist that offer and we agreed to the deal. What followed 
were several e-mails with photos of the items were going to send. I sent the 
V4SA first and a day later he sent the A1200. About two weeks later a large
box arrived from the States! A gorgeous A1200 with lovely bright white keys
and a rather sexy looking translucent case.

What followed was some more purchasing, an Indivision AGA Mk3, IDE-CF card 
from AmigaKit and a RTC. AmigaKit have had a bad rep of recent but I must
say that their service has gotten much better and I have had good 
experiences ordering from them. One other advantage is that they remove
the VAT for customers buying from outside the UK/EU, so I can always
expect a 20% discount, very nice!

Bit by bit I was building my A1200 back into a proper machine again. Next
I wanted to upgrade the TF1230 to a TF1260. The TF1230 is a perfectly good 
card and gives the A1200 a nice speed boost but I missed the smoothness and
speed that only an 060 can offer. I had a look around and found that Amiga
Store.eu were offering the TF1260 for a decent price of 170 EUR which when
converted into GBP was cheaper than anywhere else. AmigaStore.eu quickly
processed and sent my order but I was still in need of an 060. I have found
from prior experience the rev 5 060 give me the best value for money, they
are not able to go as fast as the rev4 but have the FPU which the highly
sought after rev6 does. So it was back to eBay and I found my old chip guy
and picked up a rev 5 060 that is capable of 60Mhz. Running this with the
latest version of the TF1260 firmware I can have the chip runningly smoothly
at 66Mhz. Brilliant!

After all this I need to get my A1200 back on the internet again, while the 
PiStorm offers a great way to access Wifi I wanted to stick with my TF1260.
Nothing against the PiStorm but as I have only space for one Amiga, it feels
more right to have a 'real' CPU in the Amiga. Anyways, due to having the
TF1260 my best option was to find an A314-CP. Luckily I was still part of
the A314 Discord channel and after a few inquiries on a nice chap from 
Austria built me one of the slimline A314-CPs. He was very helpful through
out the entire process and kept communication during the build and shipping.

Suffice to say once I got the card I forgot how I had originally set it up
and had to get some help from the Discord server. After a few days I some
put me in the right direction. It was a silly mistake, I thought that I 
still had to use my router's IP address in the Routes file for Roadshow.
Obviously it has to the be Raspberry Pi IP address, which is stated in the
docs online but for some reason I was not able to comprehend that until it
was pointed out to me. Red faced, I figured out how to get my A1200 back 
online again.

It has been quite the journey and a completely unnecessary one if I am
completely honest, had I just kept my original A1200 I would not have had 
to go through this journey. But at the same time I appreciate it a lot. The 
amount of help and support I have gotten from Amiga users gives has given
me a better appreciation for the Amiga scene. If there are still people like 
that out there maybe we are not all doomed after all.

Perhaps there should be a law that each ruler of a country must be an Amiga
user. Imagine how interesting that would be! Well, I have taken enough of
your time, I wish everyone of you a wonderful winter holidays and new year. 
The Amiga scene has been full of excitement and joy in 2024 and I am looking
forward to what 2025 has in store. 

@endnode

