@node rastportreview "Hardware review: RastPort"
@toc reviews
=============================================================================
@{b}Hardware Review:RastPort@{ub} - by @{"Martyn Bampton" link martynbampton}
=============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
KA02 External PCMCIA adapter (A1200/A600)

@{b}Developed By@{ub}
RastPort

@{b}Available From@{ub}
AMIGAstore.eu
amiga-shop.net
sordan.ie
retroready.one
eBay

@{b}Price@{ub}
Varies but typical best prices are 30 USD/28 EUR/35 UKP

@{b}Hardware Requirements@{ub}
An Amiga 1200 or 600 in the original case.

@{b}Test Machines@{ub}
Amiga 1200
Amiga 600

		@{"Rastport Image 1" link Images/rastport_pcmcia_04.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/rastport_pcmcia_04.iff"}

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

It's usually the case that adding anything via the A1200/A600 PCMCIA 
slot makes your Amiga take up more room at the side, just like the A500 
and its various sidecar expansions.  I used to compare it to Lieutenant 
Green (Captain Scarlet) going back and forth along the main computer in 
the Spectrum Cloudbase control room.  My chair wasn't mobile and my desk 
didn't have a lot of room so it would have been very useful to have this 
adapter from RastPort.  The adapter simply points the PCMCIA port 
towards the back of your desk and orients it vertically and it's even 
profiled to match the side of the Amiga.  Devices now face rearwards and 
any cables, like networking or SCSI, are at the back rather than taking 
up space at the side.  Left handed people may also appreciate the lack 
of clutter on the left hand side of their computer where their mouse 
would presumably sit.  While a currently a bit more expensive for UK 
folks I was able to pick one up for $30 USD which is reasonable.

@{b}Impressions and Use@{ub}

		@{"Rastport Image 2" link Images/rastport_pcmcia_01.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/rastport_pcmcia_01.iff"}

		@{"Rastport Image 3" link Images/rastport_pcmcia_02.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/rastport_pcmcia_02.iff"}

The packaging was plain but functional, just bubble wrap within a white 
box with a printed text label, but it kept the adapter safe in transit.  
Given its angular shape this is certainly appreciated.  It consists of 
two printed circuit boards joined at 90 degrees and a clear acrylic 
backing plate for strength, fixed with nuts, bolts and spacers.  The 
smaller of the boards connects to the Amiga's PCMCIA port and the larger 
is fixed to the acrylic plate and sits vertically alongside the 
computer.  The boards are joined with soldered connections and with 
metal corner brackets for support, it feels strong enough but I'd still 
treat it with care.  The circuit boards are coloured, I opted for the 
white version but you can get black too if that fits your colour 
scheme.  I really liked how it looked alongside the Amiga and it didn't 
interfere with any covers I use - however do be careful not to snag the 
adapter on any covers, that's the only problem I experienced and it's minor.

        	@{"Rastport Image 4" link Images/rastport_pcmcia_05.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/rastport_pcmcia_05.iff"}

Plugging the adapter into the Amiga was straight forward and I had no 
alignment issues.  I would be aware that the adapter is designed to sit 
with its edge flat on the desk alongside an unmodified case. If you have 
taller feet on your Amiga or have it elevated in some other way then 
you'll have to add some support to the adapter too. The adapter is 
PCMCIA compliant with all PCMCIA lines passed through unmodified as it's 
just a physical adapter, essentially an extension.  The socket has gold 
plated pins which are of different lengths to support the hot 
(un)plugging of devices and the adapter itself can be connected or 
disconnected while the computer is on. You should be able to plug in any 
PCMCIA device and it'll function as if inserted directly into the 
computer's slot.  I was able to use networking and CF adapters without 
problems and everything looks so much neater.  Attaching the RJ45 dongle 
to the network card was a bit fiddly with the card inserted so I ended 
up attaching it first then inserting the card into the adapter.  Other 
than that it's been great and I do like the fact that my Amiga's port is 
getting less wear and tear. 

Note: The RastPort adapter blocks external access to any CF to IDE adapter 
that places the CF card above the PCMCIA slot.

		@{"Rastport Image 5" link Images/rastport_pcmcia_06.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/rastport_pcmcia_06.iff"}

		@{"Rastport Image 6" link Images/rastport_pcmcia_07.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/rastport_pcmcia_07.iff"}

@{b}Summary@{ub}

A simple adapter with a modern minimalist appearance which solves one of 
the biggest gripes I had with PCMCIA card expansions, space! It might 
seem a little bit flimsy at first glance but it's strong enough if you 
use care when fitting it and inserting an removing devices.  It has the 
potential to save your port from some wear as long as you don't bump or 
snag it forcibly.  While you may have to make accommodations if you've 
raised your case for ventilation, it's mostly just fit and forget.  Oh 
and it comes in black and white.
 
Other than that it's been great and I do  
like the fact that my Amiga's port is getting less wear and tear./Â  Note:Â  The RastPort adapter blocks 
external access to any CF to IDE adapter that places the CF card above 
the PCMCIA slot.

@{b}Pros and Cons@{ub}

+ Repositions desk clutter.
+ Profiled to match the Amiga.
+ Potentially reduces port wear if handled appropriately.
+ Good build quality.
- Could catch or be pulled awkwardly if not handled appropriately.
- Blocks externally accessed CF cards mounted above the PCMCIA slot.

Other Key Points:
* Connecting cables to devices when inserted may be a bit trickier.
* May need support if you've raised your Amiga.
* Could be a bit pricey depending on where you live.

@{b}Scores@{ub}

Ease of use: 100%
Documentation/Packaging: 70%
Value for money: 70%
Overall: 80% - WhatIFF Silver

@{b}Sources and Credits@{ub}

Sold by AMIGAstore.eu: 
https://amigastore.eu/en/735-cased-pcmcia-adapter.html
Created by RastPort: https://rastport.com

@endnode

@node a600gsreview "Hardware review: A600GS"
@toc reviews
=============================================================================
@{b}Hardware Review:A600GS@{ub} - by Toki (eab.abime.net)
=============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
A600GS

@{b}Developed By@{ub}
AmigaKit

@{b}Available From@{ub}
@{"AmigaKit" system "openurl https://www.amigakit.amiga.store"}

@{b}Price@{ub}
134 GBP (inc VAT)

@{b}Hardware Requirements@{ub}
HDMI Monitor/TV

@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
N/A

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

So I've had my A600GS for about a month now. If you are thinking of 
purchasing one hopefully this will be useful. This is just my thoughts on 
it. For all the technical spec on it please head over to Amiga Kit or read 
one of the threads on EAB where people more knowledgeable than I have tested 
exhaustively.

Some background¦ I've never stopped using my Amiga for games since about 
1990. During the pandemic with more times on my hands I started using it 
for programming in assembly and in C, for which I use WinUAE so I have the 
convenience of using a modern laptop.

Firstly what I love about the A600GS, and then a few watchouts.

A600GS works straight out the box, after you have setup your Amisphere 
login. It's great to suddenly feel that you are using a machine created by 
Amiga's fanbase. You feel the your curiosity building as you search through 
its functionality. I quickly loaded a memory disk with all three of 
Hoffman's games. Just click on the adfs and there they are immediately 
inside the A600GS. Clicking on the games, playing them and creating 
thumbnail versions of save state files is a joy. No problem, just works, no 
corruptions or missing files, it just works fine. Click on screenshot and 
you can save that picture to your dashboard, which is great fun and 
personalizes the experience.

After a bit fiddling around I got my Bluetooth headphones working. Now I can 
listen to Hoffman's game music when I'm in the kitchen making a cup of tea 
before going back to the game.

Having immediate access to the game on a dedicated machine rather using my 
laptop and WinUAE seems great. I'm not sure why, it just does.

The A600GS is permanently linked to the internet. There have been a few 
firmware updates so far. The system comes with a few games preinstalled. The 
last firmware update came with Super Skidmarks which the creator has 
provided for the love of it. Suddenly developers have an immediate route to 
provide content for users. This is exciting. I feel linked in with the Amiga 
development community. The possibilities for the future! The other 
applications provided: Octamed 8, Personal Paint, DOpus4, Final Writer are 
all preinstalled. When new applications are available it's going to be so 
easy to add them from the Amisphere. Yes, obviously you might be asked to 
pay, but what a great way to support the developers. Having tried and failed 
to install Final Writer on my A1200 numerous times its great to see it here 
working straight out the bat.

So this is what I'm using my A600GS for playing games. I'm not using it for 
coding because WinUAE and the convenient of my laptop is fine for that. I'm 
not expecting the A600GS to replace my old Amigas, or WinUAE, or Amiga 
Forever. However, in future when I have a new game, hopefully Roguecraft soon
this is what I'll be firing it up on.

@{b}Now some watchouts@{ub}

There's aspects of the A600GS that feel as though they are in development, 
and hopefully improvements will come in the future. I've not managed to get 
a game working that has more than one disk. The functionality is there to 
add disks, but it has not worked for me so far.

Some ADFs, even where the games is on just one disk, don't work. Admittedly 
these are hacked versions of games I've tried, so that could be complicating 
things.

No WHDLoad. I not sure if this will be a big deal in the future if you can 
purchase/acquire effectively pre-installed software through the Amisphere.

No workbench. Personally I like Dopus 4, I've used version 5 for years. 
Amibench is preinstalled which I'm not used to, might start using it, might 
not.

The manual with the machine does not explain everything. It's OK. You'll 
find yourself going off to Youtube to see what others are managing to do. 
The A600GS has some quirks, but most of the time it's fairly intuitive.

@{b}Summary@{ub}

The A600GS is certainly Amiga Good Stuff in my book. Part of the Amiga's 
history already in my opinion. Great to have a modern working Amiga 
supported by our community. It's exciting to think where it's going to go in 
the future. If you want to experience the development as it happens now is 
the time to get one. It's fun to experience, which was always the point of 
the Amiga.

@endnode

@node a500ramreview "Hardware review:Amiga 500 2MB Memory Expansion with RTC "
@toc reviews
=============================================================================
@{b}Hardware Review:Amiga 500 2MB Memory Expansion with RTC@{ub} - by @{"Martyn Bampton" link martynbampton}
=============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
Amiga 500 2MB Memory Expansion with RTC

@{b}Developed By@{ub}
PeteAU, Mathesar and MQ666

@{b}Available From@{ub}
AMIGAstore.eu

@{b}Price@{ub}
37 USD/34 EUR

@{b}Hardware Requirements@{ub}
An Amiga 500 (not A500+) with Kickstart 1.3 or higher.  Rev 3, 5 or 6 
listed.


@{b}Test Machines@{ub}
Amiga 500 rev 6, KS 3.2
Amiga 500 rev 6, KS 1.3

                        @{"Image 1" link Images/a500_2mb_01.iff/MAIN}                  
                        @{IMG "Images/a500_2mb_01.iff"}                                
@{b}Introduction@{ub}

The most basic upgrade you can make to any Amiga 500 is a 512 KB memory 
upgrade, often with a real time clock (RTC) onboard. This 2 MB RTC 
option from AMIGAstore.eu is one of the more capable RAM expansions for 
the Amiga 500 (rev 3, 5 and 6) which will add 1.5 MB or 2 MB of 
additional RAM depending on how you want to install it. If you just add 
the card to the trapdoor as-is then you'll see an additional 512 KB Slow 
RAM. If you open your Amiga and use the provided Gary adapter you can 
add 1.5 MB. If you're willing to make simple modifications to your 
motherboard and happen to have an 8372 Agnus then you can add half a meg 
(512 KB) of Chip RAM as well as 1.5 MB Slow RAM! This will give you a 
total of 1 MB Chip RAM and 1.5MB Slow RAM and a real time clock which is 
a nice boost for the price.
                 @{"Image 2" link Images/a500_2mb_02.iff/MAIN}
                 @{IMG "Images/a500_2mb_02.iff"}
Note: A 512 KB version of this expansion is also available and the RTC 
is optional in both the 2 MB and 512 KB versions. The 512 KB version is 
listed as being compatible with all Amiga 500 motherboards, presumably 
this includes the rev 8 boards found in some later A500s.  I was unable 
to test this.

                 @{"Image 3" link Images/a500_2mb_03.iff/MAIN}
                 @{IMG "Images/a500_2mb_03.iff"}

                 @{"Image 4" link Images/a500_2mb_04.iff/MAIN}
                 @{IMG "Images/a500_2mb_04.iff"}

@{b}Impressions and Use@{ub}

The expansion card arrived in an antistatic bag which also contained the 
Gary adapter, wires, RTC battery and instruction booklet. No software 
installation is required but you will need some basic soldering skills 
and be willing to cut a trace on your motherboard if you want to add 
that additional 512 KB of Chip RAM. The instruction booklet is concise 
and easy to follow with pictures included at the end, guiding you 
through the installation of the main board, the Gary adapter and jumper 
configuration. Additional steps are required for rev 3 motherboards and 
this is detailed too. A diagram is included to show the jumper positions 
on the Gary adapter which is appreciated. I think the pictures could be 
clearer or basic diagrams provided to better show the jumper pad 
configuration on the motherboard. A PDF download with higher resolution 
pictures would be helpful.

                 @{"Image 5" link Images/a500_2mb_05.iff/MAIN}
                 @{IMG "Images/a500_2mb_05.iff"}

The expansion (88 mm x 68 mm) and Gary adapter (75 mm x 23 mm) are both 
compact and well laid out. I didn't see any resistor packs or arrays for 
reducing signal noise, however the traces are very short and I 
experienced no issues when testing with Amiga Test Kit (1.21) or in 
general use, perhaps it's just something to be aware of. To make the 
most of the 2 MB expansion you have to open up your Amiga, remove Gary, 
add the Gary adapter and then replace Gary in the adapter. This needs to 
be done if you want the additional Chip RAM and/or the 1.5 MB Slow RAM, 
else you'll only get a basic additional 512 KB of Slow RAM. Be careful 
removing Gary, insert the flat end of a spudger or a flat bladed 
screwdriver between the chip and the socket at one end and very 
carefully twist, rocking from side to side, repeat for the other end 
until the chip is free.  Don't lever the chip up or try and push the 
screwdriver further under the chip, you could gouge your motherboard!

                 @{"Image 6" link Images/a500_2mb_06.iff/MAIN}
                 @{IMG "Images/a500_2mb_06.iff"}

Insert the RTC battery into the expansion then fit the expansion into 
the trapdoor connector of your Amiga and connect the wires. There are 
three wires included, two are terminated with DuPont connectors which 
fit into the SEL0/1 headers on the expansion and Gary adapter, 
connecting them. The remaining wire is required if you opt for the 
additional Chip Ram. It's terminated on one end and is stripped and 
tinned on the other, this is the end you'll need to solder to the middle 
JP2 pad after carefully cutting the trace between pads 2 and 3. The 
other end then connects to the Gary adapter RASC header pin.  Set the 
jumpers on the Gary adapter for 1.5 MB or 2 MB (see the diagram in the 
booklet) and make sure the wires are making good contact and are not 
loose.  The system may not boot otherwise, giving you a blank or 
coloured error screen.

                 @{"Image 7" link Images/a500_2mb_07.iff/MAIN}
                 @{IMG "Images/a500_2mb_07.iff"}

That's it, test boot before putting things back together and load 
Workbench or Amiga Test Kit to check out your new RAM totals and check 
for stability. All being well you'll have an additional 1.5 MB Slow RAM 
(and 512 KB additional Chip RAM if you did the mod). The expansion 
worked fine with a TF536, RGB2HDMI and a DF0/DF1 switchless floppy 
selector - it was great to see 1 MB Chip RAM in Workbench.

@{b}Summary@{ub}

A very nice and reasonably priced RAM expansion for the Amiga 500. If 
you'd like to keep an A500 close to stock but give it a bit more than 
the usual extra 512 KB RAM for the situations that need it then this is 
a great option. However installation is a bit more challenging than 
simply opening the trapdoor slot and fitting the expansion, while adding 
the extra Chip RAM could be daunting for some. That said you always need 
to open your Amiga 500 to get that extra Chip RAM so that's hardly a 
point against this expansion.

@{b}Pros and Cons@{ub}

+ Great Value for money.
+ Add 1.5 MB without any modifications.
+ Option to double your Chip RAM.
+ Instructions included with 2 MB version, could benefit from some 
simplified diagrams.
+ Compatible with accelerators such as the TF536.
+ Other options available - without RTC and basic 512 KB.
- Need to open up your Amiga.

Other Key Points:
* Soldering skills, motherboard modification and 8372 Agnus required for 
  extra Chip RAM.
* Rev 3 Needs an additional modification/fix.
* Kickstart 1.3 or higher.
* No resistor packs visible but no issues in hours of testing and months 
  of use either.
* A different version is available for A500+.

@{b}Scores@{ub}

Ease of use: 80%
Documentation/Packaging: 75%
Value for money: 100%
Overall: 85% - WhatIFF Silver

