@node goexreview "Hardware review: GOEX SD Drive"
@toc reviews
=============================================================================
@{b}Hardware Review:GOEX SD Drive@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
GOEX drive r.2023, SD card version

@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Centurion Tech

@{b}Available From@{ub}
@{"www.centuriontech.eu" system "openurl https://www.centuriontech.eu"}

@{b}Price@{ub}
51-64 EUR

@{b}Hardware Requirements@{ub}
A500-A1200

@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
A1200

@{b}Review@{ub}
                @{"GOEX Image 1" link Images/GOEX1.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/GOEX1.iff"}
As our drives age and fail on us the GOTEK series of drives have become an
essential way of installing software and playing games. However it was
never made with the Amiga in mind,as such it can be difficult to install
one and the access to the USB port is at times a tight fit. In steps the
GOEX drive from Centurion Tech, a tailored drive repacement made for 
Amigas.

The drive comes in two variants the the standard GOEX drive r.2023 and 
more recently the GOEX on pills, the latter costs around 10 euros more
but also has the ability to put the GOEX menu as an overlay on the Amiga
output. For this review I chose the former since to use the overlay menu
requires soldering directory to the Amiga motherboard and I have a bad
history with soldering.

Ordering from the Centurion Tech website it easy, though it can be slow
so be patient. I received the drive about two weeks after purchase which
is not bad considering I am in Japan. It came in a nice little box with some
straw packing of all things, that is a new one for me!

In addition to to the GOEX drive I also purchased an OLED display in black
to put on the top of my A1200.

		@{"GOEX Image 2" link Images/GOEX2.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/GOEX2.iff"}
                @{"GOEX Image 3" link Images/GOEX3.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/GOEX3.iff"}

@{b}First Impressions@{ub}

The board appears well built, there is not much on the board aside from 
three micro chips, a piezo speaker, a rocker thumb controller and SD card 
slot.
 
Installation was very easy, the board aligned perfectly with my A1200.net 
case. 

An extra wedge is included to help align the board at the bottom where a 
floppy drive is usually screwed in. The firmware was already installed so 
all that was required was to plug in and go.

One thing to remember though, if you buy the OLDED display, feed the 
cable through the top of the case before attaching the connector. I did
not do this first and it was a bit of a tight squeeze afterwards to push
the plug between the top vents.

Once everything was in place the top fit on perfectly, I had to put the
case on a bit of an angle but after that it was a nice snug fit and looked
great with the OLED display on top. The SD card slot makes much more sense
than the GOTEK`s USB slot. It was always a struggle to get the USB stick
inserted on my previous A1200 I had to cut away at the disk slot just to 
get the USB stick all the way in. With the SD card, inserting and taking 
out cards is a much more pleasant and has the feel of inserting a floppy 
disk. The rocker on the side is another improvement over the GOTEK`s buttons 
and makes for an overall smoother experience searching for files, it also 
goes without saying the OLED display is really an essential purchase if you 
are dealing with many files.

Compared to the days of using a GOTEK drive, finding the right button and
checking on the side and fumbling with a USB drive, the GOEX is a much
better product. This is product that has been made for Amiga users and it
really shows.

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

If you already have a GOTEK, then it might not be worth your money investing
in a GOEX, if you do not have a GOTEK yet or are getting frustrated with
your GOTEK then the GOEX is a perfect replacement for either your ageing
floppy disk or GOTEK. It is more expensive than a GOTEK but you do get a
more refined product that is better suited to the Amiga. I just love the
feeling of inserting an SD card into it, it feels more authentic than using
a USB stick.

@{b}Scores@{ub}

Ease of use: 78%
Documentation/Packaging: 83%
Value for money: 88%
Overall: 83% - WhatIFF Silver

@endnode

@node electrowarereview "Hardware review: Electroware PSU"
@toc reviews
=============================================================================
@{b}Hardware Review:Electroware PSU@{ub} - by @{"Martyn Bampton" link martynbampton}
=============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
Amiga Power Supply (50 W)
Amiga Power Supply (Boost 50 W)

@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Electroware

@{b}Available From@{ub}
Electroware (c64psu.com)
retropassion.co.uk
eBay

@{b}Price@{ub}
Depends on model and options but as reviewed:
Normal (with AC cable and Protect & Adjust LED module): 68 USD/65 EUR/55 UKP
Boost (with AC cable): 89 USD/85 EUR/69 UKP

@{b}Hardware Requirements@{ub}
An appropriate computer :)  At the time of writing PSUs are available for:
* Amiga 500/600/1200/CD32
* C64/C128/VIC-20/1541-II/1581
* Atari 520ST,1040ST/260ST/SF314/SF354/MegaST
* ZX Spectrum +2A/+2B/+3

@{b}Test Machines@{ub}
Amiga 500 (TF536)
Amiga 600
Amiga 1200 (TF1260)
CD32 (with an adapter but a PSU with CD32 DIN connector is available)

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

When I first powered up an Amiga after it had been sat for a long time 
(a @{b}long@{ub} time) the very first thing I did was test the voltages coming 
out of the power supply.  The last thing I wanted to do was send 
loadsavolts where they should never go.  Fortunately all the voltages 
were correct so I set the system up and cautiously powered it on to be 
greeted with the familiar Kickstart screen. Phew, that worked, but the 
question in my mind was "for how long?"

This prompted me to get a modern replacement power supply I could trust 
and which would cope with an expanded Amiga (the original 25 W to 35 W 
PSUs are a bit underpowered).  While several options presented 
themselves, most seemingly based on a Mean Well 50 W PSU, I was rather 
impressed with those Polish company Electroware sell. They offer quite a 
few features such as protection circuits, higher 5 V current ratings and 
even dual outputs for powering two devices. Each PSU comes in a compact 
black or grey housing with a detachable mains cable and a switch.

Listed features include:
* Based on Mean Well PSUs (RPT-60B for the normal version, 50 W/60 W peak).
* Carefully calibrated for Amiga 500 reference load.
* Active & passive over voltage protection for main +5 V line.
* Over current protection for all output lines.
* Fully isolated & fused on AC side.
* Power On/Off switch.
* Long output cable (1.8 M) with rectangular DIN 5-pin plug (or round 
  pin plug for CD32 version).
* Detachable input AC cable for all versions (cable optional).
* Weight only 0.4 KG (half of the original PSU's weight).

With Protect Module:
* Trimmer for 5 V voltage fine tuning in range: 4.9 - 5.3 V (values read 
  with A500 reference load).
* Power good status LED (green).
* Redundant, fast over voltage protection for 5 V line.
* Redundant, resettable over current protection for 5 V line.
* Voltage spikes suppression with ultra-fast TVS diode.
* Additional output ripple reduction by low-ESR capacitor filtering.

@{b}Impressions and Use@{ub}
                @{"Image 1" link Images/electroware_psu_01.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/electroware_psu_01.iff"}
The PSUs each arrived in a well bubble wrapped corrugated cardboard box 
which contained the PSU, a small leaflet  (showing basic information 
with the pin outs) and the mains cable I selected for my region.  It was 
a welcome surprised to see how compact they were in person and how 
easily they fit on my desk.  They both measure approximately 11 cm x 7 
cm x 7 cm.  After years of the bricks from Commodore this was a new 
experience!  Turning the normal unit over I saw the adjustment hole for 
the 5 V rail on the bottom, this is where you can trim the voltage 
should it ever drift away from 5 V, the main voltage rail in Amigas.  
The Boost version includes the adjustment module by default and its 
adjustment hole is on the side where the output cable exits the 
housing.  Both have rubber plugs to cover the hole which you remove 
before inserting a flat bladed screwdriver to make any adjustments 
between 4.9 V -- 5.3 V.  I didn't have to make any changes.
                @{"Image 2" link Images/electroware_psu_02.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/electroware_psu_02.iff"}
                @{"Image 3" link Images/electroware_psu_03.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/electroware_psu_03.iff"}
I attached the mains cable and powered  each unit on to check the 
voltages.  As expected all the voltages were correct and within 
millivolts of the required values (+5 V, +12 V, -12 V).  Excellent! I 
proceeded to "neatly organise" my cables, set up the power supplies on 
my desk and hook them up to my Amigas.  The power switch, which is a 
rocker switch, gives a satisfying click when pressed and is located on 
the power cable side at the top.  The switch is red for the normal 
version and black for the Boost, it's a handy way to tell them apart at 
a glance as they are otherwise identical in appearance if you opt for 
the same colour housing.  The computers functioned perfectly and 
continue to do so a year later. Since "working without issues" could be 
somewhat subjective I carried out some tests and recorded the results.  
They are included here along with the listed specifications:

@{b}Specifications@{ub}

Power

It should be noted that the 12 V rails on the Boost version are reduced 
in order to "boost" the 5 V rail's capacity.  I contacted Electroware 
(great customer support, thank you) about this and they recommended 
moving as much to the 5 V rail as you can.  Most newer floppy drives 
seem to be 5 V only and you can get 5 V versions of most CPU and case 
fans should you need them.

+--------+-----------+-----------+-----------+------------+
| PSU    | +5 V (A)  | +12 V (A) | -12 V (A) | Total (W)  |
+--------+-----------+-----------+-----------+------------+
| Normal | 4.0/4.4*  |  2.0/2.2* | 0.5 0.55* | 50.0/55.0* |
+--------+-----------+-----------+-----------+------------+
| Boost  | 8.0/10.0* |    0.5    |   0.15    | 47.8/57.8* |
+--------+-----------+-----------+-----------+------------+
Peak*
 
@{b}Temperatures and Voltages@{ub}

These are not extensive or exhaustive tests by any means, I simply 
wanted to see how the PSUs respond under idle and load for various 
configurations, consider it anecdotal.  Electroware say the units run 
"COLD", not just cool but cold so I wanted to test this.  The Amiga was 
booted and left idle for an hour, then the temperature was recorded as 
Idle 1.  The system was then given an intensive CPU load for half an 
hour, after which the temperature was taken again as Load.  Finally the 
Amiga was left idle again for an hour, then the final temperature was 
measured and entered as Idle 2.  An average of the ambient temperature 
was also recorded.  The voltages remained stable throughout testing.

A1200 TF1260
+--------+-------------+------------+-----------+------------+----------+
| PSU    | Ambient (C) | Idle 1 (C) | Load (C)  | Idle 2 (C) | 5 V Rail |
+--------+-------------+------------+-----------+------------+----------+
| Normal |    18.0     |    41.5    |   45.0    |    43.0    | 5.0      |
+--------+-------------+------------+-----------+------------+----------+
| Boost  |    18.0     |    24.5    |   25.0    |    25.0    | 4.9      |
+--------+-------------+------------+-----------+------------+----------+

A500 TF536
+--------+-------------+------------+-----------+------------+----------+
| Normal |    19.0     |    33.5    |   35.0    |    35.0    | 5.0      |
+--------+-------------+------------+-----------+------------+----------+

The A600 and CD32 have also been using these power supplies over the 
past year, however no values have been recorded.  I used a separately 
purchased adapter to convert the square 5 pin DIN to the round 4 pin DIN 
the CD32 uses.  It was the same here too:  Both systems worked fine and 
were stable no matter what I ran on them and the PSUs never got 
worryingly warm to the touch.

@{b}Summary@{ub}

These are compact and capable PSUs based on trusted Mean Well power 
supplies and built with quality components.  The Protect & Adjust Module 
provides some extra benefits if that's  important to you.  The Boost 
version is also worthy of consideration but be aware that you'll have to 
make sure your 12 V rails are lightly loaded. There was very little 
variation in voltage or temperature for each test system, regardless of 
load.  While the normal version ran noticeably hotter than the Boost 
version when powering a TF1260 A1200 it wasn't alarmingly hot and 
remained stable.  Electroware do recommend the Boost version for 
expanded set ups and in testing it consistently had the lowest 
temperatures, though not what I would call cold.  If you're looking for 
a new power supply then these units are certainly worth considering.

@{b}Pros and Cons@{ub}

+ 50W PSU, twice the original's capacity.
+ Protected 5V rail, all rails filtered and stablised.
+ Neither PSU ever felt hot, just warm.
+ Repair is supported and spare parts are available.
+ Safe!  Fused, meets safety standards.
- Boost 5V rail 8A rating is at the expense of  12V rail capacity.

Other Key Points:
* Dual versions available for powering two devices.
* CD32 version available but an adapter is recommended for flexibility.
* Boost recommended for expanded set ups and does run cooler.
* It's not cheap but that's because it's not @{b}cheap@{ub}, you get what you 
  pay for.

@{b}Scores@{ub}

Ease of use: 100%
Documentation/Packaging: 70%
Value for money: 76%
Overall: 82% - WhatIFF Silver

