@node ibrowsereview "Software review: IBrowse 3"
@toc reviews
=============================================================================
@{b}Software Review:IBrowse 3@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
IBrowse 3.0

@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Oliver Roberts
Stefan Burstoem

@{b}Available From@{ub}
@{"https://www.ibrowse-dev.net" system "openurl https://www.ibrowse-dev.net"}

@{b}Price@{ub}
43 USD

@{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
Any Amiga with FastRam and an internet connection
MUI
AmiSSL

@{b}Test Machine(s)@{ub}
Amiga 1200 OS3.2 / TF1230
Amiga 1200 OS3.2 / TF1260
Amiga 1200 OS3.2 / PiStorm
V4 Standalone Coffin OS

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

While browsing on a classic Amiga may not be the most pleasant experience
especially if you have a lower spec Amiga and/or no graphics card there are
still some advantages to being able to surf the web on your real Amiga.

Aminet is the first one that springs to mind and FrogFind! is another.

In 2024 the pickings are slim for classic Amigas, especially if you are
looking for one that is up todate. In that regard there is only one choice
, IBrowse. However, unlike browsers on other platforms it is not free, you 
are looking at around 43 USD for purchasing a license for IBrowse. While 
this is a fair bit of cash for people, I thought I would take the plunge 
and see if it was worth my hard earned cash.

IBrowse currently stands at release 30.8 (22 Dec 2023), there have been 8
releases prior to that with the 9th release being IBrowse 2.5. I will not
go over all the changes through the various releases but will concentrate
on the latest version.

Release 30.8 brings the following updates:

	* Net: Fixed cases where HTTP(S) connections could fail, crash 
          and/or trash memory when the transfer size is not known.
	* Prefs: Fixed errors where the URL Prefs page would freeze/get
          stuck.
	* Javascript: Stack overflow protection for MorphOS.
	* GUI: Updated Danish, Italian, Polish, Russian, Spanish and
	  Swedish catalogues.
	* Install: Added Images drawer as 2.x to 3.0 migration option.
	* Install: Improved the messages about upgrading to make them 
	  more specific.

More general improvements are:
	
	* A unification of IBrowse 2 and IBrowse 3
	* Redesigned HTML parser
	* Improved HTML engine
		- Layout and rendering improvements that include tables
		  lists, and superscript/subscript
	* Hotlist Multi-aliasing (OS4.1)
	* Early Data/Zero Round Trip Time Resumption (0-RTT)
	* Better GIF animation playback
	* AmigaOS3.2 Context sensitive mouse pointers
	* NList GUI consistency
	* Improved Preferences window

@{b}Installation@{ub}

Before installing IBrowse you want to make sure that you have MUI installed
if not, do this first as IBrowse requires MUI to be present to function. The
default install of MUI uses rather large buttons with IBrowse so I copied
over the MUI Images and settings from my ClassicWB which makes for a much
more compact IBrowse display.

Aside from MUI you also need the latest version of AmiSSL installed which 
can always be found from Aminet.

@{b}In Use@{ub}

Above are listed many of the improvements but how does it translate to real
world experience. From the get go, I noticed IBrowse was generally more 
responsive and showed improvements in the rendering of websites. Previous
versions had trouble rendering tables and the layout of websites but with 3a
many of those have been improved.

In addition, websites seemed more responsive and rendered quicker that in 
the past. Of course this will also depend on your internet connection 
bandwidth and CPU. However I found even on a TF1230 and A314-CP the speed was 
acceptable.

Just to give an idea for comparison I run my Workbench in PAL Hires Laced
in 64 colours. I imagine if you have a PiStorm then you will see a much bigger
improvement.

I feel I do have to address though what IBrowse is for, because the classic 
Amiga even with a fast CPU and/or RTG graphics will still not be able to 
handle a lot of the modern websites. So if you are looking to watch YouTube
or the news websites then you are going to be disappointed. But if you wish
to access Aminet or look up some information using FrogFind then IBrowse will
be perfectly fine. There has also been a trend for creating websites remini-
scent of websites built in the 90s to early 2000s.

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

While there is not much choice regarding modern web browsers for the classic
Amigas, it is still an essential tool in 2024. So much software is uploaded
and updated on Aminet that if you have a connected Amiga then going directly
to source makes much more sense that downloading on your PC/Mac and then
transferring the data via the CF slot. There is also an inherent joy in 
still being able to browse the internet on an Amiga in 2024. If you are 
sitting on the fence then download the demo but while I would have liked the
price to be a bit cheaper it is still worth every penny. I find myself often
using IBrowse just to look up some info or download some tools or files.

Hopefully the team will continue improvements into 2025, but the bottom line
is if you want to browse on your Amiga in the best way possible, IBrowse 3a 
is your only choice and a good one at that.

@{b}Scores@{ub}

Ease of use: 90%
Documentation/Packaging: 85%
Value for money: 83%
Overall: 86% - WhatIFF Silver
  
@endnode

@node flashmandelreview "Software review: FlashMandel `Vamped Edition`"
@toc reviews
=============================================================================
@{b}Software Review:FlashMandel `Vamped Edition`@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
Flash Mandel `Vamped Edition`

@{b}Developed By@{ub}
FlashMandel - Dino Papararo
FlashMandel Vamped Edition - Marcel Maci

@{b}Available From@{ub}
@{" Aminet " system "OpenURL https://aminet.net/package/gfx/fract/FlashMandelVE"} https://aminet.net/package/gfx/fract/FlashMandelVE

@{b}Price@{ub}
Free

@{b}Hardware Requirements@{ub}
68080 V2/V4 Equipped Amiga or V4 Standalone

@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
V4 Standalone 1GB 100Mhz

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

Released in 2001 FlashMandel has been around for a while and over the years
has been ported to various Amiga platforms: Amiga OS3.0 and  OS4.0. In 2023 
a new version was started with the aim of taking advantage of the Vampire 
cards/standalone systems.

Originally programmed by Dino Papararo, the latest version has been done by
Marcel Maci aka RedBug. The full name is FlashMandel "BurningShip" Vamped 
Edition, or FMVE "BurningShip". Marcel has termed FMVE as being a `hybrid` 
programme, meaning the programme will run on classic systems but it will 
auto  detect if Vampire hardware is available and provide Vampire specific 
features and optimisations.

@{i}So what are these new features?@{ui}

Below is a short extract from the readme file ...

Vampire optimizations, e.g.:
- Use 3-operant functionality of FPU and additional registers.
- Parallelize Mandelbrot/Julia set calculation by using free cpu/fpu 
  latencies.
- Speed improvement is around 30% compared to "classic" version.
- Possibility to switch forth and back between classic and optimized via 
  menu or keyboard.
- Direct and fast drawing to screenbuffer (with possibility to switch back 
  to AmigaOS functions if desired).

New fractals:
- Multibrot (including fractional powers > 1.0)
- BurningShip. 
- Buddhabrot (Nebulabrots).

New calculation algorithms (available for all fractals):
- Brute force
- Tiling (original algorithm by Dino Papararo)
- Boundary trace
- Random drawing (for Nebulabrots)
- Symmetry (for main view, if possible)

New coloring algorithms (besides "classic iteration count") for 24bit modes:
- Renormalized iteration count
- Cyclic Sinus Coloring (like FlashMandelNG)
- Three channel 24bit coloring for Nebulabrots

New file format:
- Support for Deep IFF (ILBM) Images (24bit truecolor)
- New data chunk to include all calculation data
- Histogram file for Buddhabrot (with RLE compression)
- Backwards compatibility with old formats (pictures and palettes)

New features / functions:
- Real time visualization of orbits (in main view for all fractals)
- Nebulabrot calculation can be stopped and resumed
- Bailout value can be modified

New pictures:
- Sample pictures for new fractals have been included
- Nice splash screen and new icon 

Installation is as easy as dragging the FlashMandelVE drawer to your desired 
location, there is no need to run an installer. Within the directory you 
have example pictures,  palettes, Docs and the the FlashMandel programme. 

For this review I used an emulated A1200 and a V4 Standalone.

@{b}Getting Started@{ub}

Upon loading FlashMandel you are presented with default Mandelbrot fractal,
to zoom in click on an area and use the menubar, choose Calculate and Zoom.
Or a keyboard shortcut of right Amiga key and Z. Rendering time is very fast
on my V4SA, taking only a few seconds to calculate the zoom. A big difference
from my Amiga days in the 90s when I was using an 030. Changing the screen
resolution to a higher one will cause a significant drop in rendering speed.

You are not limited to the Madelbrot fractal, going to Options from the menu
bar and Fractals will allow you to choose from several other fractals: 

	* Julia Set
	* Madelbrot
	* Multibrot
	* Burning Ship
	* Nebula
	* Anti Nebula

Of the six I was unable to get Anti Nebula to work, though my V4SA is the
1GB version, the current core I am running (10000) is not comaptible with
ApolloBoot at the moment. So I only have 512MB of ram available, once a
new version of ApolloBoot is available and I can run a newer core that sees
the 1GB ram I will try AntiNebula again and update it in a future issue.

My favourite fractal is Nebula, it creates a very realistic looking nebula
esque image but does take a lot of time to render. You also need to be 
running a screen mode that supports 24BIT screen depth. Saying that, it is 
worth it as the image is truly stunning and beautiful to look at.

Under the Options menu there are many things that can be changed, that will
speed up the rendering time or add more detail. Being one who did not do so
well in Maths class some of the options are beyond my understanding.

Though I was able to play around with the settings to find ones that I liked
but best part of the software is the exploration of the fractals. Zooming
into the fractal searching for something that looks unique is a fun activity
and is made more so with the ease of Flash Mandel VE and the power of the V4
machine.

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

There is much to explore in FlashMandel Vamped Edition and is nice to see
software being released that takes advantage of the V4 hardware. While the
readme states it should work on non-V4 systems I was unable to get it to
run on my A1200, though I suspect this is due to a lack of an FPU. If you
are a V4 owner then I recommend downloading FlashMandel VE and enjoy the 
beautiful images you can render.

@{b}Scores@{ub}

