@node govdreview "Software review: GoVD Virtual Desktop"
@toc reviews
=============================================================================
@{b}Software Review:GoVD Virtual Desktop@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
GoVD

@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Krzysztof Donat

@{b}Available From@{ub}
@{" Aminet " system "OpenURL https://aminet.net/package/util/wb/GoVD"} https://aminet.net/package/util/wb/GoVD

@{b}Price@{ub}
Free/Donation

@{b}Hardware Requirements@{ub}
OS3.2

@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
V4 Standalone OS3.2
UAE A1200 3.2

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

In 2021 Amiga OS 3.2 was made available to Amiga users and along with it
came new features such as windows that you can move off the screen, a new
GUI kit in form of Reaction, updated datatypes and a more advanced version
of Multiview. Of course these are only a few of the advances that we got
with the OS update. Since then the amount of software that takes advantage
of the new OS has been a bit thin on the ground, in issue 12 we reviewed
DrawerGenie which was one of the few applications taking advantage of 
OS3.2. So it was with great interest that I saw the post of EAB about a
new piece of software for OS3.2 machines, GoVD - Workbench with virtual
desktops. Now this is something that truly peaked my interest, as I use the
Workbench a lot for my software, especially with the V4SA and it can get a
bit crowded at times. I can hide or reduce a window but there has never
been a virtaul window system similar to what you get with MacOS ... until
now ... well almost.

Developed by Krzysztof Donat, it can be downloaded from: 

=> www.bitplan.pl/govd/index.html

You can find his other work there as well such as, GoADF!, RADManager,
GoShell, Galactica, ColorPicker, CurrencyConvertor, GoVars and EmptyADF.

So what is GoVD? Essentially it creates a maximum of 8 virtual Workbench
desktops, not screens. So, if you have Brilliance open for example it will
not work with GoVD, only applications that use the Workbench screen will be
able to use GoVD.

When you have unarchived the file, you will have a drawer containing three
files: GoVD, CoVD-conf and a readme. Double clicking on GoVD will bring up
a small button bar on the bottom of your Workbench screen, by default there
are four. If you wish to use 8 you need to register the software.

The software is very simple and intuitive to use, click on a number and 
then open an application (Remember only one that opens on the Workbench 
will work), then click on one of the other buttons to switch to another
virtual Workbench hiding the application and it's window associated with
that button.

@{b}Configuration@{ub}

GoVD is highly configurable via the GoVD-conf, from this programme you have
five tabs: General, Buttons, Layout, Excluded Windows and About. Under
General you can change the number of virtual desktops between 2,4, 6 and 
8. Show Workbench on all virtual desktops and show other Workbench windows
such as drawers on all virtual desktops.

The Buttons tab allows you to change the size of the buttons and remove
the numbers or change them to letters. Under the Layout tab you can choose
where to position the window with the buttons, very handy if you have a 
dock on your Workbench. You can also change the orienation from horizontal
to vertical.

Finally the Excluded tab has two panels where you can add windows by 
process and windows by title. Overal a very comprehensive list of settings
allowing ou to customise GoVD to your liking.

To be able to use these changes you need to register the software via the
bitplan.pl website and the Donate button.

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

Amiga OS3.2 has been created a more modern Workbench experience but it is
most exciting when we get software like GoVD that use the power of OS3.2
and give us features only found in modern OSes. I have found that GoVD
has become an essential part of my Workbench experience. It is great
especially for those running in a lower Workbench resolution but is also
useful for people who have a high res Workbench. I find that running GoVD
on my V4SA is a very smooth and pleasant experience, though it shines best
when running on a PAL Hires screen. 

It has quickly become a tool I cannot imagine using my Amiga without. For 
example my current Workbench has IBrowse on virtual Workbench 2, Protext 
on virtual Workbench 3 and IMP on virtual Workbench 4. Switching between 
is easy and becomes second nature quickly. I love the fact that if I want 
to look up something in IBrowse it is ready there on another virtual screen.

Sometimes it is little things that make a big difference and in this case
I feel it is so. Please download and give it a try, if you like it also
consider donating to the developer for his hardwork.

@{b}Additional:@{ub}

It seems to have an issue with OS3.2 on V4 machines, the button graphics 
get corrupted. This is apparently due to the AROS.rom so hopefully it can 
be fixed in the future. While the corruption is not pretty the programme 
still works.

After running GoVD on my A1200 with TF1260 I encountered random freezes. 
I initially thought this was due to running my 060 over 50 Mhz but after 
I disabled GoVD the freezes disappeared. This did not occur with my TF1230 
so it could be related to the 060.library perhaps, hopefully this is 
something that can be addressed in future updates.

@{b}Scores@{ub}

Ease of use: 95%
Documentation/Packaging: 85%
Value for money: 100%
Overall: 93% - WhatIFF Gold

@endnode

