@node roguecraftreview
@toc gamereviews
=============================================================================
@{b}Game Review: RogueCraft@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================
@{b}Product Name@{ub}
RogueCraft
@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Ricki Sickenger (Programming)
Henning Ludvigsen (Artwork)
Jogier Liljedhal (Soundtrack)
Hoffman (Sound Effects)
Andy Roberts (Production Stuff)

@{b}Available From@{ub}
@{"https:///thalamusdigital.co.uk" system "openurl https:///thalamusdigital.co.uk"}
@{b}Price@{ub}
Digital Download 9.99 USD
Boxed 19.99 - 44.99 GBP
@{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
ECS+ 1MB Chip RAM + 1MB Other RAM (or 2MB Chip RAM)
@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
Amiga 1200 TF1260
Apollo Computer V4+Standalone

@{b}Review@{ub}

In the last issue (WhatIFF? 3.14 August 2024) we interviewed the guys behind
RogueCraft, since then the game has been officially released in physical and
digita form. As such it would be remiss of us to not review the game in this
issue. 

If you haven't been living under a rock it would have been hard to have 
missed the launch of RogueCraft. In development for over a year and various
demos being released the final version was available for purchase in 
September 2024. For those of you who have been living under a rock and do 
not know of RogueCraft, it is a turnbased roguelike game where you explore
and fight in procedurally created dungeons. Originally created in 1980 by
Michael Toy and Glenn Wichmna with later contributions by Ken Arnold it was
made for Unix systems and was freely available. The Amiga eventually got its
own version in 1986 releaed by Epyx.

Now in 2024 we are treated to an updated version.

The game is available as a digital downlaod for 9.99 USD or in a boxed 
version which ranges from 19.99 GBP to 44.99 GBP. I went for the 19.99 
version and it came with a glossy cardboard box, game CD (for CD32 users), 
colour game manual, Thalamus sticker, Roguecraft postcard, A3 poster and 
floppy disk label.

If you go for 29.99 you get in addition, Roguecraft bookpuck, Badger Punch
postcard, Roguecraft sticker sheet and a floppy disk of the game. The final
tier for 44.99 GBP comes with the all of the former plus pin badge, 
Roguecraft t-shirt and a plastic chicken.

		   @{"GOEX Image 1" link Images/RogueCraft1.iff/MAIN}
                   @{IMG "Images/RogueCraft1.iff"}

The story goes as such ...

"For time immemmorial, legend has told of a dark, deadly dungeon containing
unimaginable horrs and riches beyond belief. Enough riches and maigic to 
make you a king ... or more ...

Through many tirlas and perils, you are now standing a the entrance of a 
dark and mystical dungeon far from where you started. You, Zendar, a fighter
a mage, or uh, a rogue, are ready to defeat the monsters and gather the 
riches waiting below.

You just need to take a leak first ..."

Upon loading the game you are presented with the a gorgeously drawn title
screen and three options: Start Game, Instructions and Credits. You are
treated to a lovely title song by Logier Liljedhal. You can use the keyboard
or joystick to start the game, there is no need to choose your form of 
input. Selecting Start Game will bring up the character selection screen:
Warrior - Easy, Rogue - Medium and Wizard - Hard. Rogue has special abilty
of teleport and Wizard magic missiles. Warrior has a heavy sword. From there
you can enter into the game.

                        @{"GOEX Image 2" link Images/RogueCraft2.iff/MAIN}
                        @{IMG "Images/RogueCraft2.iff"}
                
                
                   @{"GOEX Image 3" link Images/RogueCraft3.iff/MAIN}
                   @{IMG "Images/RogueCraft3.iff"}
                
The game in presented in a 3D isometric view which is a welcome upgrade from 
the 1986 top down view. You can use either the keyboard (Yes!) or a joystick
to move around. The hold the spacebar will allow you to choose the potions 
you have picked up that are placed around the dungeons. Green will restore
yur health, Red and Blue have different effects each time:

	Extra Strength
	Reveal All
	Strong Ale
	Clear The Room
	Freeze Time
	Teleport
	Chickenize

There are also crystals that can be picked up, red will increase maximum
health and blue will increase maximum strength. You will also find hearts
to increase your health bar by one point.

The aim of the game is to explore the dungeons, find the key to get to the
next stage and kill all the enemies. There is also a secret room in each 
dungeon that is not shown on the current dungeon map. You have to look for
walls that look a bit different to the others. Fighting is a simple affair
walk into the direction of your enemy and keep at it until they are dead.

Some reviewers have commented that the controls take a little getting use
to, I find that I confused for a minutes until muscle memory set in.
Instinctivly you want to press right to go right, but in RogueCraft it is
up to go right and so on, which makes sense since it is set to an isometric 
view.

This brings me on the graphics, the first time I saw the screenshots I 
thought it was an AGA game, they have truly done wonders with the ECS
hardware. There is so much detail in each screen, from flickering fires
to bubbling green pits. The character animations are done well making
for a very highly polished game. When I sit down to play the game it takes
me back to my days of HeroQuest with my mates, the tile pieces of the game
are very similar with everyone fighting to get to the end of the level. If 
you are reading this Douglas then you will know what I mean. With each level
being procedurally generated it makes the game great for replay and keeps
you on your toes.

I played the game on my A1200/030 and 060, V4+ Standalone and under 
emulation the only time that I had issues was when running it on FS-UAE, I
found by changing the settings to an 020 CPU the flickering issues
disappeared. So it seems that any CPU setting above an 020 in FS-UAE will
cause graphical glitches i.e. flickering of the screen.       

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

I love this game, everything about it so well done, from the graphics to the
audio. The gameplay is set perfectly and the procedurally generated levels
make sure it never gets boring. If you buy one game this year then I suggest 
RogueCraft.

@{b}Pros and Cons:@{ub}
+ Well balanced gameplay
+ Graphics are very well done and give a proper atmosphere to the game
+ The procedurally generated levels mean that you go back again and again
+ The music suits the game perfectly and I always enjoy listening to it

@{b}Scores@{ub}
Gameplay: 95%
Graphics: 90%
Sound: 89%
Overall: 91% - WhatIFF Gold

@Endnode

@node untanglereview
@toc gamereviews
=============================================================================
@{b}Game Review: Untangle@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================
@{b}Product Name@{ub}
Untangle
@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Grezgorz Kraszweski
@{b}Available From@{ub}
@{"https://aminet.net/package/game/wb/untangle" system "openurl https://aminet.net/package/game/wb/untangle"}
@{b}Price@{ub}
Free
@{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
Any Amiga as long as your are running Workbench
@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
Amiga 1200 TF1260
Apollo Computer V4+Standalone

@{b}Review@{ub}

In October of 2024 Polish programmer Grezgorz Kraszweski released the game
Untangle. It is a logic puzzle game that runs on the Workbench screen,
something we do not see so often. In this issue we also talk to Grezgorz
about his creation. The premise of Untangle is to move the dots around so
the lines that connect them do not intersect anymore. This type of game
exists on other platforms but there has not been any versions of this style
of game until now.

Being a Workbench game the graphics are very simple but do not be put off
by this as the graphics hide a highly addictive game. There is not much to
the gameplay mechanics, click and drag the dots with your mouse until you
have no more intersecting lines. When you have successfully "untangled" the
lines the screen will flash and you will be automatically taken to the next
stage. The first 15 levels do not provide too much trouble but are a good
way of leading the player into how to solve the puzzles. Later levels do
become quite the head scratchers but due to the nature of the gameplay which
encourages experimentation, it does not become a chore.

At the bottom of the play window you have the number of current
intersections, how many moves you have taken and the total time for that
particular level. You are also able to save your game progress, once a file
has been created the game will automatically start from where you last
finshed off. This makes it ideal if several people are playing the game on
the same Amiga and want to keep their progress/score separate.

I played the game in PAL Hires and PAL Hires Laced, while the game worked
prefectly well in Hires I recommend playing it in at least Laced or some
other higher resolution. It will make it easier when you come across the
more complex puzzles.

It can be hard to review a game like Untangle due to the simple/sparse
graphics and very simple gameplay but that does not detract from the fact
that it is a very addictive and enjoyable game. When I am writing articles
and I need a break Untangle is a great way to break up my time. The fact
that it also saves your progress automatically makes it a great title that
you can dig into and out of whenever you want. To top it off the game is
available for free. Grab your spouse, child or friends and have a go at
this addictive game together.

@{b}Pros and Cons:@{ub}
+ Simple and addictive gameplay
+ Runs on Workbench
+ Save feature
- Need a higher resolution to enjoy the game more

@{b}Scores@{ub}
Gameplay: 80%
Graphics: 70%
Sound: 0%
Overall: 75% - WhatIFF Bronze

@endnode

