@node tf1260tower "How to install a heatsink on TF1260 when using a Tower case"
@toc guides
=============================================================================
@{b}How to install a heatsink on TF1260 when using a Tower case@{ub} - by: @{"John Scolieri" link johnscolieri}
=============================================================================

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

I originally had my TF1260 in my Amiga 1200 case with a heatsink only but I 
recently got hold of a full (FPU &MMU) Rev6 and wanted to try overclocking 
it occasionally for heavier demos etc.

After a few quick measurements it was clear that I'd need to put my TF1260 
in a tower to make room for a fan setup so that's what I did. After 
initially setting up my tower and using it for only a few hours I noticed 
the heat sink on the 060 started sliding down slightly as the thermal paste 
heated up there wasn't anything physically keeping the heatsink (& soon to 
be fan) from being a victim to gravity in the tower.

After browsing my fav Amiga forums I couldn't find the info I needed so I 
started a thread on the TF1260 forum at: 

https://exxosforum.co.uk/forum/viewtopic.php?f=65&t=6880 and luckily a 
TF1260 user that goes by go0se had setup gerber files for a lower & upper 
support brackets as follows:

1- First step is to download the gerber files at the above link (post no.4) 
   and get the upper & lower brackets manufactured at your favourite 
   fabricator or you can send me a message as I had to order 5 min so I've 
   got 4 extra I can send out to fellow TF1260 users for the cost of 
   shipping.

2- Carefully take off your CPU (don't forget your antistatic pad & wrist 
   band) and place your bottom bracket as in Pic1.
	             @{"Pic 1" link Images/PIC-1.iff/MAIN}
                     @{IMG "Images/PIC-1.iff"}

3- Reinstall your 060 as in Pic2.
                     @{"Pic 2" link Images/PIC-2.iff/MAIN}
                     @{IMG "Images/PIC-2.iff"}
4- Install a thin layer of thermal paste to the underside of the top metal 
   bracket as in Pic.3. I used a Q-Tip to spread the paste evenly.
                     @{"Pic 3" link Images/PIC-3.iff/MAIN}
                     @{IMG "Images/PIC-3.iff"}
5- Carefully install top metal bracket on 060 as in Pic.4
                     @{"Pic 4" link Images/PIC-4.iff/MAIN}
                     @{IMG "Images/PIC-4.iff"}
6- Make sure to line up the lower and upper bracket holes as in Pic5.
                     @{"Pic 5" link Images/PIC-5.iff/MAIN}
                     @{IMG "Images/PIC-5.iff"}
7- Install CPU fan as in Pic6. Ensure your CPU fan has mount spacing of 55mm 
   to line up with the adapter brackets.
                     @{"Pic 6" link Images/PIC-6.iff/MAIN}
                     @{IMG "Images/PIC-6.iff"}
   Note: It's your choice to purchase a 12V or 5V fan though obviously when 
   in a tower case there is easy access to get power for the CPU fan from 
   the PSU. As an option you can even get 12V directly on the TF1260.

8- Lastly you can use either small plastic nuts & bolts or what I did was 
   just bend some epoxy coated wire to secure the lower and upper plates as 
   in Pic7. Ensure you do both sides of the CPU.
                     @{"Pic 7" link Images/PIC-7.iff/MAIN}
                     @{IMG "Images/PIC-7.iff"}
Cheers,
G. Scolieri
@endnode

@node blitzbasicbasics "Blitz Basic Basics Part 2: A Simple Demo"
@toc guides
=============================================================================
@{b}Blitz Basic Basics Part 2: A Simple Demo@{ub} - by: @{"Andy Vaisey" link andyvaisey}
=============================================================================

Welcome to the second part of @{b}Blitz Basic Basics@{ub} where I hope to get you 
coding and creating simple demos and games using the excellent Blitz Basic 
2 (BB2) programming language!

If you've read and followed part 1, you should now have a simple development 
environment on an Amiga (real or emulated) ready to begin! In part 2 we are 
going to create a very simple demo that loads and runs automatically, 
displays a bitmap image while playing some music, before exiting when a key 
is pressed.

Please note, this and future code is written in a way to make it easier for 
a @{b}beginner@{ub} to read and understand. There will be ways to make it more 
compact, quicker and/or better, but at this stage getting something up and 
running is more important to feel a sense of achievement! Although nothing 
fancy or competition winning, this instalment of Blitz Basic Basics will 
help you learn how to:

= allow your program to be run from Workbench
= use the fast @{b}BLITZ@{ub} mode in BB2
= set up a display
= load a bitmap image
= show the bitmap on the display
= load some music
= play the music
= handle a keypress on the keyboard
= compile and test our code
= create an @{b}executable@{ub} to spread your warez!

In the @{b}BBB P2@{ub} drawer on disk accompanying this article, you will find:

= a program named @{b}BBB Demo 1@{ub}
= a Blitz2 source code file named @{b}Demo1Code.bb2@{ub}
= a drawer called @{b}data@{ub} containing the files needed for the demo

Go ahead and run the @{b}BBB Demo 1@{ub} file. After some loading, on screen 
should be the WhatIFF? logo with a piece of saxophone music playing (the 
music is something I wrote back in 1992 and is the first time it's ever 
been heard by anyone else except me!).  Once you've had enough of this 
extravaganza(!), hit space on the keyboard to exit back to Workbench/
AmigaOS.

So, let's explore how this very simple single screen demo was put together.  
Load the BB2 editor/compiler on your Amiga (that you should already have 
installed), click on @{b}OkeeDokee@{ub} in the splash window and then select @{b}Load@{ub}
from the @{b}Project@{ub} menu. Locate and load the file called @{b}DemoCode1.bb2@{ub} in 
the @{b}BBB P2@{ub} drawer.

First observations about the main editor/compiler display and code?

= Anything on a line after a semi-colon is text only and not regarded as 
  code that the Amiga can run.  It's similar to older versions of BASIC, 
  where you may have seen the REM command, short for @{b}Remark@{ub}, which are 
  comments and notes only. Effectively, when the code is compiled and run, 
  these comments are not used and left out to save memory.

= Some words are highlighted in a different colour. These words are the 
  @{b}instruction set@{ub}, the main BB2 commands. The rest of the code is in a 
  different colour, usually black.

= There is a list of words down the right hand side. Think of these as a 
  short cut to the different sections (subroutines) of the code. If you 
  click on one of these words, the editor skips to that section in the code 
  and you will see these words have a dot [.] at the beginning of them. 
  Usually, these @{b}shortcuts@{ub} are for calling or branching to longer 
  subroutines, but for this example I have used more of them so you can jump 
  around the code more quickly!

What is this code actually doing then?  The first two commands are:

NoCli
WBStartup

The @{b}NoCli@{ub} command stops the Amiga opening a default CLI window when 
testing the code in the BB2 coding environment. This command is ignored 
when you create a fully functioning and self-executing file when development 
is complete as a CLI window won't open then.

The @{b}WBStartup@{ub} command is very important. Since the Amiga has a friendly, 
multitasking operating system, it is likely that at some point the user of 
your program may want to run it from Workbench. If you do not include this 
command and the user attempts to run it from Workbench, your program WILL 
crash possibly taking AmigaOS with it. It's safer to include this command 
than not!

Next in the code, we have the @{b}constants@{ub} section:

.constants
#COPPER_MAIN = 0
#PALETTE_MAIN = 0
#BITMAP_MAIN = 0
#MODULE_MAIN = 0

What on earth is all that nonsense and what is a constant anyhow?! A 
constant is a numerical value that NEVER changes during the operation of 
your program and are usually named to make things easier to read. In Blitz2, 
constants are @{b}declared@{ub} using the hash symbol at the start. So, wherever in 
the rest of the code example you see @{b}#BITMAP_MAIN@{ub}, BB2 knows the value to 
be zero and which always remains zero. Of course, you could assign another 
numerical value, but I'm using zero as we're only using one bitmap and 
computers always start counting from zero! If I used a second bitmap, then 
the constant for that would have a different name would equal one.

After the constants, I've set some @{b}variables@{ub}:

.variables
BWIDTH = 320  ; bitmap width
BHEIGHT = 256  ; bitmap height
BDEPTH = 5  ; bitmap colour depth

Eh? Variables are word or letter representations for numerical values so, 
wherever you see in this code example the word @{b}BWIDTH@{ub}, BB2 knows the 
value to be 320. Unlike constants, variables can be changed at any time by 
performing a mathematical operation on it or simply by giving it a new value 
using the equals symbol.  And notice I've used a semi-colon at the end of 
each line so I can make a comment explaining what the variable relates to.

A few notes before we look further at any more code. You may have noticed 
that I've used capital letters for my constant and variable names. It's not 
strictly necessary to do that, but it's my preference to keep things neat 
looking. Also, in BB2, variable names can be set as a specific type with a 
suffix,  for accuracy. We're not going to worry about that for now as BB2 
will happily assign a @{b}type@{ub} internally, but it will crop up in future 
articles and will be explained then. Finally, an admission: my variables in 
this example could actually be constants since they're not going to change 
in this code, but I wanted to show and describe constants and variables and 
the difference between them! So there!

Back to our code example, next we have:

.createbitmap
BitMap #BITMAP_MAIN,BWIDTH,BHEIGHT,BDEPTH

This @{b}BitMap@{ub} command creates an @{b}object@{ub} or display on which we can show 
graphics (whole images, sprites, blitter objects and so on) and everything 
after that command tells BB2 how to create the object. The information BB2 
needs to create this object/display is:

= a bitmap number to give the object
= the bitmap width 
= the bitmap height
= the bitmap depth (number of colours)

In our example demo, we are giving the bitmap a number of zero (the constant 
BITMAP_MAIN), a display width of 320 (the variable BWIDTH), a display height 
of 256 (the variable BHEIGHT) and a display depth of 5 (the variable 
BDEPTH). If you are wondering why I'm sounding convoluted and using terms 
such as object and display instead of just saying @{b}screen@{ub}, it's because in 
BB2 a @{b}screen@{ub} and associated commands relates to a Workbench (Intuition) 
screen on which you open windows and that is something different!

We could have directly @{b}hardcoded@{ub} those numbers values along with the 
@{b}BitMap@{ub} command like this:

BitMap 0,320,256,5

But the beauty of using constants and variables is that you can use easy to 
remember words in a nice list at the start of the code that, if need to be 
changed, can be easily found and altered, instead of having to search 
through the code to find the bit that needs to be changed.

Also, the benefit of using constants and variables comes in not having to 
remember or write down which number relates to which resource.  For example, 
imagine you create or load five bitmaps. Each bitmap may have its own 
number. Instead of you having to remember which bitmap has which number, by 
using a constant, you can assign a descriptive name. In our code example, 
bitmap 0 is called @{b}BITMAP_MAIN@{ub} as it's the main bitmap we're using. You 
can do the same with other data as well such as copper displays, music, 
sound samples and so on.

Following on using that logic, you can see I've done the same for the bitmap 
size as well, using variables set at the start. As already mentioned, since 
those values won't be changing, they could technically be constants.

The other part of the bitmap object display setup that needs explaining is 
the @{b}depth@{ub}, in effect the number of colours we want on bitmap display. In 
our example it is set as @{b}5@{ub} which equates to a 32-colour display. How does 
this work? The value of depth to the power of 2 gives the number of colours, 
as below:

Depth 1 = 2 colours
Depth 2 = 4 colours (2x2)
Depth 3 = 8 colours (2x2x2)
Depth 4 = 16 colours (2x2x2x2)
Depth 5 = 32 colours (2x2x2x2x2)
Depth 6 = 64 colours (2x2x2x2x2x2)

Next in the code, we load some assets (the graphics and music):

.loadassets
LoadBitmap #BITMAP_MAIN,data/logo.iff
LoadPalette #PALETTE_MAIN,data/palette.col
LoadModule #MODULE_MAIN,data/music.mod

Most of those commands should be pretty much self-explanatory! We are 
loading a bitmap screen drawn in a graphics package, the palette from that 
bitmap saved separately from within that graphics package and a music module 
written in a music tracker. You can see we are again using our previously 
declared constants to assign easy to remember names to these loaded assets 
instead of using numbers throughout our code! All of the assets are loaded 
from a drawer called @{b}data@{ub} which MUST be located in the same parent drawer
/disk as our code file or final executable, otherwise loading will fail.

Next we have a wait command:

VWait 250

This is a vertical blank wait. On old CRT screens, the image is drawn by an 
electron beam moving left to right, top to bottom. Any changes you make to 
the screen while it is being drawn will probably cause a flicker. Therefore, 
it is useful to wait until the screen has been drawn and the beam is off the 
screen before making any changes. There is a bit more going on but for now 
that's all we need to know.

However, on this occasion we are not actually making any changes to the 
screen but are using the command as a @{b}timer@{ub}. The @{b}250@{ub} equates to around 5 
seconds (every 50 vertical blanks is around a second). The reason for this 
wait is because we have been accessing the disk to load our assets and we 
need to be sure that disk access has finished before we issue any more 
commands. If our code carries on before the disk access completes, we risk 
a crash! IMPORTANT!!! After loading anything in BB2, wait at least 5 seconds 
before doing anything else especially when using the next command, explained 
below:

Now we enter a different @{b}mode@{ub} with the following code:

.blitzmode
BLITZ
BlitzKeys On

The @{b}BLITZ@{ub} command puts your program in Blitz mode! This means Amiga 
operating system is deactivated and your code now takes over the whole 
machine, you now have full control over all those powerful chips inside 
your Amiga! This does mean that your Amiga will no longer multi-task or be 
able to access files from disk but the benefit of BLITZ mode is that your 
code executes much quicker and you have access to potent display features 
such as smooth scrolling and dual-playfields!

Although we have turned the operating system off, the command @{b}BlitzKeys On@{ub} 
still allows us to @{b}read@{ub} the keyboard to check if the user has pressed a 
key.

BLITZ mode can be temporarily stopped to re-enable disk access and multi-
tasking features if needed and this will be covered in a future article.

Now we need to actually display our previously loaded bitmap:

.initcopperlist
InitCopList #COPPER_MAIN,44,256,$00005,8,32,0

.displayscreen
DisplayPalette #COPPER_MAIN,#PALETTE_MAIN
DisplayBitmap 0,#BITMAP_MAIN
CreateDisplay #COPPER_MAIN
Use BitMap #BITMAP_MAIN

What on earth is all that?! BB2 was originally written before the advent of 
AGA chipset Amiga's so later versions of BB2 added new libraries for @{b}CopList@{ub} 
commands, replacing the old @{b}Slice@{ub} commands in order to take advantage of 
the newer Amiga AGA chipset. These @{b}CopList@{ub} commands are fully compatible 
with older chipsets and only need to be initialised in code once. The 
@{b}CopList@{ub} library is used to display our graphics. 

So what is this @{b}InitCopList@{ub} command? It creates a display and 
allocates memory we can show our bitmap on the display. All the numbers 
after the command relate to the following parameters (and yes, some of those 
CopList parameters could have been constants!):

InitCopList CopList#,ypos,height,flags,sprites,colours,custom

The @{b}CopList#@{ub} is the number of the copper list we want to use. In the 
example code, we are using our #COPPER_MAIN constant. The @{b}ypos@{ub} and @{b}height@{ub}
parameters define the vertical section of the screen our display will take 
up. In our code example, the display is at 44, the very top of the 
copperlist and is 256 lines in height.

The flags paramter holds information about the screen resolution and number 
of colours. For this code example, we have $00005 which equates to a low 
resolution screen with 32 colours. In future articles, this flags parameter 
will be explored further with an explanation how to change screen 
resolutions and the number of colours.

The @{b}sprites@{ub} parameter should always be @{b}8@{ub} as that is the maximum number 
of sprites the Amiga can display. The @{b}colours@{ub} parameter sets the number 
of colours in our copper list, in our case @{b}32@{ub}. The @{b}custom@{ub} parameter 
should be set to @{b}0@{ub} for now.

The @{b}DisplayPalette@{ub} command copies our previously loaded colour palette 
(#PALETTE_MAIN) into the CopList we have initiated (#COPPER_MAIN) and the 
@{b}DisplayBitmap@{ub} command tells the computer we want to use our @{b}CopList@{ub} to 
display our previously loaded bitmap (#BITMAP_MAIN).

Finally, we issue the command @{b}CreateDisplay@{ub} to set up a new screen display 
with the @{b}CopList@{ub} display library and tell the @{b}CopList@{ub} to use our bitmap 
with @{b}Use Bitmap@{ub}.

Phew!  Almost done now! Next in the code we have:

.playmusic
PlayModule #MODULE_MAIN

Hopefully that needs no explanation?! OK then, this command plays our 
previously loaded music module!

And finally we have:

.mainloop
Repeat
VWait
Until RawStatus (#KEY_SPACE)
End

Most programs, whether a simple demo such as this or a complicated game, 
have a main loop. The main loop is where the computer is instructed to 
continually execute a series of tasks. For example, in a game the main loop 
may jump to a series of subroutines that check the joystick, update the 
display, control animations, play sound effects, check collisions and so on.

Our main loop here begins with a @{b}Repeat@{ub} command and ends with an @{b}Until@{ub}
command. All the loop does is keep waiting for a vertical blank until the 
user presses the space key on the keyboard, checked by using the @{b}RawStatus@{ub}
command and built in constant #KEY_SPACE. When the user presses space, the 
code exits the loop and encounters the @{b}End@{ub} command which, funnily enough, 
ends the demo and returns to whatever the computer was doing before running 
the demo. Before I forget, most main loops will have a VWait command in 
there somewhere so make sure everything is running smoothly so I put one 
in, even though our main loop isn't actually really doing anything at 
present!

That's the code, but how do you test it? Go to the @{b}Compiler@{ub} menu and 
select @{b}Compile & Run@{ub} and the demo should run. When you've had enough, 
press space and the demo should exit back to the BB2 editor.

The more adventurous amongst you will probably want to start experimenting 
with this code and I emphatically say @{b}go ahead@{ub}! Nothing beats tinkering 
with other people's code. Why not try replacing the bitmap or music? I've 
included another bitmap and music file in the @{b}data@{ub} drawer for you! If 
nothing else, if you are a graphics or music person, you now have the 
basis of a simple display system to release your own graphics and music; no 
more waiting on a lazy coder or using a nasty @{b}demo maker@{ub} to display your 
hard work for you!

Although I've already created a self-running executable (BBB Demo 1), if 
you make any changes and want to create a new executable, there is an option 
in the @{b}Compiler@{ub} menu to do just that! Just make sure you create the 
executable in the same parent drawer/disk as the @{b}data@{ub} drawer!

In next part of @{b}Blitz Basic Basics@{ub} we will build on this simple display 
code, reusing some of the commands we've already looked at while introducing 
more commands! As a slight side note, my saxophone music in the demo is 
running at a tempo slightly quicker to which I originally wrote it 30 years 
ago. This is to do with the way BB2 plays music modules via a library that 
insists on timing using a vertical blank instead of CIA (a chip inside the 
Amiga that deals with system timings). We'll deal with this in future as 
well, perhaps even installing a better music library for BB2 to use.

Until next time!

@endnode

@node avoidingclicks "Avoiding clicks'n'pops in your MODs"
@toc guides
=============================================================================
@{b}Avoiding clicks'n'pops in your MODs@{ub} - by: @{"Roald Strauss" link roaldstrauss}
=============================================================================
Back in WhatIFF? issue 2.11 I wrote a small article about the various 
options we have available for reducing @{fg highlight}quantisation noise@{fg text} in 8-bit audio.

We learned that quantisation noise is what we get when we reduce the @{fg highlight}bitdepth@{fg text} 
of the audio from @{fg highlight}16 bits@{fg text} (or more) to @{fg highlight}8 bits@{fg text}. It happens because 8 bits 
aren't enough to represent the original analogue signal. The noise we hear is 
actually the sound of the missing data. To reduce quantisation noise, we can 
use @{fg highlight}SSRC@{fg text} (Shibata Sample Rate Converter) to move the noise up to a 
higher frequency that most of us (in our age group) can't hear. Or we can use 
the @{fg highlight}LAQ@{fg text} (Least Amount of Quantisation) method to move a lot of the noise 
down to a lower frequency that most of us can't hear.

And finally, we should also mention @{fg highlight}the 14-bit trick@{fg text} as an option.

In issue 3.14 of WhatIFF? Magazine I wrote a follow-up to that article, with 
some new insights about quantisation noise reduction, that I'd gained since 
I wrote the first article. The follow-up article also included a section 
about dealing with the @{fg highlight}harmonic overtones@{fg text} we get when using low samplerates. 
This kind of noise happens because there's no kind of interpolation filter 
on Amiga.

We can't get rid of harmonic overtones (when using low samplerates), but we 
can make them less annoying to listen to, by tuning them to the actual 
frequency of the sampled instrument.

In my previous article, I gave a wrong formula to calculate the harmonic 
overtone: tonefrequency*2^n

I've since learned that the correct formula is @{fg highlight}(tonefrequency*2,1)*2^n@{fg text}
You can also avoid harmonic overtones by using a high enough samplerate. 
B-2 and above should be good.

In this 3rd and last article in the series, I'll round things up by 
addressing the 3rd type of noise we have to deal with on Amiga: 
@{fg highlight}Clicks'n'pops@{fg text}.

But before continuing, please note that these articles are strictly about 
8-bit Protracker MOD music (or MEDs). They are about reducing noise in 
"8-bit stock Amiga audio".

The goal is to create music that is attractive for Amiga gamedevs, and the 
primary filetype used by Amiga gamedevs is the Protracker MOD format.

@{fg text}You may have noticed that certain MODs (or MEDs) on Amiga sometimes produce 
a click here and a pop there. You may even have grown so accustomed to these 
clicks'n'pops, that you just consider them to be a natural and charming part 
of @{fg highlight}"The Amiga Sound"@{fg text}, whether it's on a subconscious level, or something
you're fully aware of.

I personally notice any kind of noise in audio quite a lot - and these 
clicks'n'pops annoy my tiny audiophile brain just as much as quantisation 
noise does. Especially when I've created a nice MOD in Milkytracker that I 
am somewhat proud of, only to discover that it's @{b}full@{ub} of clicks'n'pops when 
listening to it on my Amiga.

I've therefor often pondered about whether anything could be done about this 
problem, but I never dived into any actual research until now.

During my research I ended up exploring many options and made quite a lot of 
discoveries along the way, which I will now share with you here. I will list 
all the different conditions that cause these clicks'n'pops to occur, and 
then describe various techniques you can use to work around them.

@{fg highlight}@{b}The looping bass@{ub}@{fg text}
We'll start with a sample of a looping deep sine wave. It'll look like this 
when playing a single tone.

                 @{IMG "Images/sine1tone.iff"}

If you use this sample to play different notes in the same channel, the 
resulting output may look somewhat like this:

                 @{IMG "Images/sine3tones.iff"}

Every time a new note plays, the previous note is interrupted, and the 
sample is played from the beginning, with the samplerate of the new note. 
It's easy to see on the visual representation of the audio, where a tone is 
interrupted and a new tone begins. Especially when the previous tone is 
interrupted when the sample is at its highest amplitude. Because then the 
@{fg highlight}audio jumps@{fg text} from max amplitude to zero from one data-point to the next. 

And it is this jump that cause the click. 

@{fg highlight}That's simply the sound such a large jump makes@{fg text}.

This might puzzle a few readers, because the whole model with interrupting 
notes with new notes, is used in quite a lot of different tracker filetypes 
- which would logically mean that we should be hearing such clicks'n'pops 
all over the place when listening to tracker music in general. But we don't. 
We only hear them when playing MODs on Amiga. (Or other Amiga filetypes such 
as MED and DBM files).

There is quite clearly a difference between these Amiga filetypes and PC 
filetypes: The PC filetypes have a fancy feature called @{fg highlight}volume-ramping@{fg text}, 
which basically @{fg highlight}smoothens@{fg text} such large jumps in amplitude when they're too 
big. So we don't hear clicks'n'pops when playing these filetypes on a PC 
where they originate from. Like for example if you play an XM in FastTracker 
II, there are no clicks'n'pops. However, if you play the same XM with 
DigiBooster Pro on Amiga, then it will most likely be full of clicks'n'pops. 
Because there's no volume-ramping in DigiBooster Pro, but there is in 
FastTracker II.

Even if you create a MOD on Amiga with clicks'n'pops, it will usually be 
free of clicks'n'pops if you play the same MOD with a random PC player.

So yes, it can be rather frustrating to be an Amiga musician, if you care a 
lot about producing clean sound.

But let's look into ways to avoid these clicks on Amiga when we have no 
volume-ramping available. There are plenty of workarounds we can use, and 
which one to use depends on the scenario. In this particular case; 

@{fg highlight}The looping bass@{fg text}, we can use a simple and commonly used workaround: 
The @{fg highlight}portamento to note (3xx) command@{fg text} for each new note. That way, instead 
of interrupting the previous note and starting the sample from the beginning 
again, the waveform will continue to play while gliding up/down to the next 
note.

                 @{IMG "Images/sine3xx.iff"}

As you can see, this approach completely eliminates all the large jumps in 
amplitude, and therefor the clicks are gone now. We'll call this first 
anti-click technique @{fg highlight}@{b}"The portamento method"@{ub}@{fg text}.

@{fg highlight}@{b}Fadeout solves nothing@{ub}@{fg text}
But a constant bass sine isn't always what we want. Sometimes we want a 
short bass note instead. So the next logical idea will be to try to @{fg highlight}fade out@{fg text} 
the tones between each note with @{fg highlight}A0x@{fg text} commands. That way, the volume should be 
low or even zero when the next note is played, and it should therefor 
logically eliminate all the clicks'n'pops.

                 @{IMG "Images/sinefade.iff"}

But two things may seem surprising here. The first surprise is that, despite 
fading out the volume of the previous note before playing the next note, 
there are @{fg highlight}still clicks@{fg text} that are @{b}equally@{ub} loud and just as annoying as in 
the very first scenario. Even if waiting @{fg highlight}several seconds@{fg text} with @{fg highlight}total silence@{fg text} 
before playing the next note! This makes absolutely no sense, since the 
previous tone @{b}is@{ub} definitely faded out now.

The other surprise is that a lot of @{fg highlight}smaller clicks'n'pops@{fg text} seem to have joined 
the party too now.

So fading the tones seems to have resulted in the exact opposite of what we 
were aiming for: It has @{b}increased@{ub} the amount of clicks'n'pops instead 
of removing them. @{b}What's going on???@{ub}

Well, it turns out there's a @{fg highlight}limitation@{fg text} (some say bug) in Protracker: When a 
new note is played, the volume on that channel is reset to whatever volume 
the sample has. That makes sense of course. But the problem is, that the 
volume is turned up @{fg highlight}before the previous note stops playing@{fg text}. Which means that 
the last few milliseconds of the previous tone is turned up just before it's 
interrupted. This basically renders the whole volume fade-out approach 
completely useless, since it has no effect on the clicks'n'pops at all. We 
still have the exact same problem as in the first scenario, which is clearly 
visible when we zoom in:

                 @{IMG "Images/sinefadezoom.iff"}

There is a workaround for this problem though: Once the previous note is 
faded out, we can @{fg highlight}play another sample@{fg text} that only has a few milliseconds of 
data at zero amplitude and zero volume. That way, when channel volume is 
changed before playing the new note, it doesn't matter that it plays the 
zero amplitude snippet from the previous sample first.

There are @{fg highlight}3 drawbacks@{fg text} to this approach though:

1: We need a whole row for this extra "anti-click" sample.
2: We need to use up a sample slot too.
3: It may interrupt the previous note before we want it to.

But apart from those drawbacks, it does effectively remove the click. Let's 
call this workaround @{fg highlight}@{b}"The silent sample trick"@{ub}@{fg text}.

You might get the idea of using @{fg highlight}EDx to delay@{fg text} the silent sample, to make 
the previous tone a few ticks longer before interrupting it. But no: There's 
another bug in Protracker here: Although EDx does indeed delay the sample 
with x ticks, the resetting of the channel @{fg highlight}volume@{fg text} is @{b}not@{ub} delayed. Volume 
is set at the very first tick of the row regardless. So EDx doesn't help us 
at all here. The previous tone will be silenced at the beginning of the row 
with the silent sample regardless of any EDx value.

Ok, so that explained why the clicks where still there, and we found a 
workaround to fix it: @{fg highlight}The silent sample trick@{fg text}. But what about all 
those additional smaller clicks then?

Well, all these smaller clicks are caused by the @{fg highlight}volume fade A0x@{fg text} commands, 
because that's how @{fg highlight}sensitive@{fg text} audio is without volume-ramping. @{fg highlight}A0x@{fg text} works by 
reducing volume @{fg highlight}x@{fg text} values per tick (except the first tick) for each row. 
If tickspeed is set to @{fg highlight}F06@{fg text} then @{fg highlight} A01@{fg text} will decrease the volume with @{fg highlight}1@{fg text} value @{fg highlight}
5@{fg text} times for that row, and @{fg highlight}A0F@{fg text} will decrease the volume with @{fg highlight}15@{fg text} values @{fg highlight}5@{fg text} 
times. So it's not a smooth fade, but rather a kind of staircase fade that 
produce a lot of smaller jumps in the amplitude. So the higher @{fg highlight}A0x@{fg text} value, the 
bigger the jumps, and therefor the louder the clicks.

                 @{IMG "Images/sinefadezoom2.iff"}

These circumstances will probably make you try to settle with @{fg highlight}A01@{fg text} to get the 
least amount of these clicks'n'pops - and that might be fine in some cases. 
But you may also find that even A01 can cause clicks'n'pops that annoys you, 
or else you may find that A01 doesn't fade fast enough.

So what kind of workarounds can we find here? Well... since the clicks'n'
pops happen because there's a jump in the sample amplitude, it's obvious 
that the solution is to somehow avoid these jumps. In other words: If all 
the tick locations are placed where the sound amplitude is (near) zero, 
then we'd be all set. Because then the jumps wouldn't be noticeable.

@{fg highlight}@{b}The "magic" frequency@{ub}@{fg text}
Since tones are frequencies, and samplerates are frequencies, and tempo is 
a frequency too, then it is possible to find a tone-frequency that matches 
the samplerate and tempo, so that the each (half) wavelength is placed 
exactly where the tick offsets are. So when @{fg highlight}A0x@{fg text} turns down 
volume by @{fg highlight}x@{fg text} steps, it does so where the amplitude is zero, 
and @{fg highlight}thus doesn't cause a click@{fg text}.

But how to calculate what this frequency is?

Well, if you (like myself) don't know anything about the inner workings of 
the Amiga, then you'll probably try to calculate this frequency like this:

Let's say we have a track playing at @{fg highlight}125 bpm@{fg text}. Then we know that 
each @{fg highlight}beat@{fg text} is 60000/125 = @{fg highlight}480 ms@{fg text}, which means 
each @{fg highlight}row@{fg text} is 480/4 = @{fg highlight}120 ms@{fg text}, and each @{fg highlight}tick@{fg text} 
is 120/6 = @{fg highlight}20 ms@{fg text}.

At a samplerate of @{fg highlight}16574,27 Hz@{fg text} that means each tick is 16574,27*0.02 = 
@{fg highlight}331,48 samples@{fg text}.

We can then calculate that we'll need a tone frequency of 16574,27/331,48 = 
@{fg highlight}50 Hz@{fg text} (or a multiple thereof) in order to make sure all the 
tick locations are placed at the zero amplitude offsets in the sample. And 
yes, this absolutely works! @{fg highlight}Suddenly all the clicks'n'pops are gone@{fg text}, 
no matter how rough a fade we do. Even interrupting the tone and playing a 
new one doesn't give any clicks! Listening to this deep click-free bass sine 
is so amazing that it's difficult to believe it's a MOD in Protracker we're 
listening to.

If you're a master on Amiga audio though, and therefor know a great deal 
about the inner working of the Amiga, then you'll most likely find the 
above calculation method silly, and instead calculate the frequency like 
this:

First, you'll find the @{i}actual@{ui} tempo on Amiga, which is 
@{fg highlight}1773447,5/(floor(1773447/tempo)+1)@{fg text}.
 
So if we've set a tempo of @{fg highlight}125 bpm@{fg text}, then the actual tempo on Amiga will be 
1773447,5/(floor(1773447/125)+1) = @{fg highlight}124,99629969 bpm@{fg text}.
And then to get the actual samples per tick, we have to divide the sample-
rate with @{fg highlight}(actual_tempo/2,5)@{fg text}. So actual samples per tick becomes 
16574,27/(124,99629969/2,5) = @{fg highlight}331,49521308 samples@{fg text}.
And the frequency then becomes 16574,27/331,49521308 = @{fg highlight}49,998519876 Hz@{fg text}.
As you can see though, the difference between the two calculation methods is 
tiny (0,001480124), and doesn't affect the outcome of this experiment at all.

Anyway, we can sadly only produce this "magic clickless frequency" for one 
specific tone-frequency (or a multiple thereof) for each tempo setting. And 
that means it's not a whole lot useful in praxis. It basically only serves 
as a proof that this technique works... at least for some samples.

So how can we achieve the same awesome anti-click effect with any other kind 
of sample? Well, I had @{fg highlight}4 ideas@{fg text} on how to do this, and did extensive 
experiments with all of thems.

@{fg highlight}@{b}Idea 1: "The burned volume-ramp".@{ub} Edit the sample, and boost the amplitude at
the exact tick locations with the exact amount that the A0x command has, 
and then fade to normal. In other words; add a kind of static volume-ramping 
burned into the sample to counter the A0x effect.@{fg text}

This requires extremely precise timing that is tricky to get right, and it 
also renders the sample useles for any other kind of Axy commands. Meaning, 
it'll produce clicks'n'pops with any other combination of Axy commands - or 
if you don't use any Axy commands at all. In other words, idea 1 is useles.

@{fg highlight}@{b}Idea 2: "The sample-fade in/out trick".@{ub} Edit the sample and adjust the wave
-form to make sure the amplitude is (near) zero at the tick locations, by 
fading the sample in and out around the tick offsets.@{fg text}
This is less demanding in regards of accuracy, but the fade ins'n'outs that 
are necessary to prevent clicks, will alter the sound to such a degree that 
it becomes equally annoying as the clicks'n'pops. Some will probably say 
even worse. So idea 2 is worthless too.

@{fg highlight}@{b}Idea 3: "The stretch'n'shrink trick".@{ub} Edit the sample and stretch or shrink
each snippet of audio between tick locations to make sure the amplitudes 
end up (near) zero at each tick location.@{fg text}

Sounds promising at first, thinking that the strething'n'shrinking of 
snippets will "just" result in some kind of vibrato effect, which might 
even sound cool? But sadly no. This approach too will alter the sound to 
such a degree that it is useless.

@{fg highlight}@{b}Idea 4: "The tick frequency trick".@{ub} Create an additional frequency matching 
(half) the tick sample size, and mix it with the audio in order to get the 
amplitude at the tick-offsets placed at zero.@{fg text}

@{b}This is it!@{ub} By reading the data-point values at each tick-offset, and 
then applying a counter frequency between each tick-offset, we can alter 
the sound so that all the tick-offsets will have an amplitude of zero. This 
@{b}will@{ub} cause the signal to go outside the scope sometimes, but we 
can try different tone-frequencies, tempos and volume adjustments until it 
stays inside the scope. And best of all: The sample still sounds fine, since 
the signal we're adding is at such a low frequency that we can't hear it.

This will require us to @{fg highlight}"unroll"@{fg text} the short looped bass though, so that it 
becomes a much longer sample. In other words, it'll take up more space.
Another disadvantage is that the sample can only be used at a @{fg highlight}specific 
samplerate and tempo@{fg text}. So if you want to use this approach for a bass, then 
you'll need a bass @{fg highlight}sample for each tone@{fg text} you want to play. You might be 
fine with this - I personally am - because quality matters more to me than 
filesize. But I understand if you feel you'll be using too many samples and 
too much space with this approach, and therefor want to hear about other 
options. 

Personally though, @{fg highlight}the tick frequency trick@{fg text} is exactly the kind of trick 
I was looking for. Because it allows me to do fades and cut off notes 
without clicks, and I've really been missing that.

But nothing is ever easy, is it? No it isn't.

It turns out, there's a sample-trigger delay on Amiga, which means the tick 
offsets doesn't match our precalculated locations where we made sure the 
amplitude is (near) zero. In one experiment, playing a 16574 Hz sample, 
judging solely by listening, the delay was about 8-9 sample-points. But in 
another experiment, the delay was about 11 sample-points. That may not sound 
like much, but it's enough to affect the clicks'n'pops. So by deleting this 
amount of sample-points in the beginning of the sample(s), the clicks were 
gone again on my Amiga.

Curious to find a formula that lets us calculate how many sample-points this 
delay is, I reached out to a couple of masters on the topic. But although I 
did get some interesting info, I never found a useful formula. It seems the 
delay varies too much depending on various factors.

In other words: If you want to use @{fg highlight}the tick frequency trick@{fg text}, then you have 
to listen to the MOD with the playback library that's going to be used, and 
then delete the number of sample-points it requires for the clicks to be 
gone. There is no way to guarantee a click-free MOD with this approach on 
all players out there.

@{fg highlight}@{b}The sample fade-out trick@{ub}@{fg text}
So the next idea, in order to avoid all the small clicks'n'pops that the @{fg highlight}Axy@{fg text} 
commands creates, will probably be to simply @{fg highlight}fade out the amplitude in the 
sample data itself@{fg text}.

This approach of course @{b}also@{ub} means we'll be using more bytes for 
sampledata than a short looped sine, since we'll be including the fade-out 
in the actual sample data now. And we will probably also want to have more 
than one sample, to avoid the fade-outs varying too much in speed when you 
play the bass sample at different notes.

The advantage with this approach is that, if the tone is interrupted, it'll 
most likely happen at a low amplitude, and thus won't cause a click. The 
disadvantage is that fading out the amplitude in an 8-bit sample will create 
more quantisation noise.

@{fg highlight}@{b}The sample playthrough method@{ub}@{fg text}
A method similar to the sample fade-out trick, is to have samples of the 
same instrument, in varying lengths - but without a (long) fade-out. This 
will work just as the sample fade-out trick works, except without the 
additional quantisation noise since we don't fade the amplitude in the 
sample.

@{fg highlight}@{b}The sample-offset method@{ub}@{fg text}
What about an option that only requires us to use @{fg highlight}a single sample@{fg text}, while 
still avoiding clicks'n'pops? Are there any such option available? 

Yes there is. :-)

Let's go back to the initial deep bass sine - but unroll it so that it 
becomes a longer sample. If you can shape this deep bass sine so that each 
256 data-points matches the zero amplitude points of the tone-frequency, 
then you can use the @{fg highlight}sample-offset (9xx)@{fg text} command to start the sample at 
various offsets - and thus make it reach the end quicker, resulting in a 
shorter tone.

For example, if we use a samplerate of @{fg highlight}16574,27 Hz@{fg text}, then we'll need a tone 
frequency of 16574,27/256 = @{fg highlight}64,743242188 Hz@{fg text} - or a multiple thereof, in order 
for the @{fg highlight}9xx@{fg text} offsets to match the zero-amplitude points of the sample.

While this method works quite nicely, it comes with several disadvantages 
too:

1: Since the tone-frequency has to match the tick offsets, it'll be 
   difficult to get the tone in tune with the other instruments in the 
   track.
2: Though it does eliminate cut-off clicks (since the sample gets to play 
   through before the next note), it doesn't help us with fade pops.
3: And the method will only work with certain types of instruments: The ones 
   that has very little variation.

@{fg highlight}@{b}Details matter@{ub}@{fg text}
Lack of volume-ramping makes everything @{b}really@{ub} sensitive to clicks'n'pops. 
If we start a sample with a non-zero data-value - then it will create a 
click when starting the sample. If we end a sample with a non-zero data-
value - it will create a click when the sample is done playing.

Samples should @{b}always@{ub} begin with two data-values of zero, and the last 
twp data-values (in a non-looping sample) should also be (at least close 
to) zero.

@{fg highlight}@{b}Summary@{ub}@{fg text}
All in all we ended up exploring a whole 9 different techniques for avoiding 
clicks'n'pops. 3 of them were useless, which leaves us 6 options to choose 
from.

Each method has its own ideal usages. Some are great for removing fade-pops. 
Some are good for avoiding cut-pops. Some are optimal for short looped 
samples while others are best for "unrolled" samples. Here's an overview:

                              | Eliminate |
                              | Fade| Cut |
                              | Pop | Pop | Best for
------------------------------+-----+-----+--------------------------------
@{fg highlight}The portamento method@{fg text}         | No  | @{fg highlight}Yes@{fg text} | Looped samples
------------------------------+-----+-----+--------------------------------
@{fg highlight}The silent sample trick@{fg text}       | No  | @{fg highlight}Yes@{fg text} | Looped samples
------------------------------+-----+-----+--------------------------------
@{fg highlight}The tick frequency trick@{fg text}      | @{fg highlight}Yes@{fg text} | @{fg highlight}Yes@{fg text} | Chords and single tones
------------------------------+-----+-----+--------------------------------
@{fg highlight}The sample fade-out method@{fg text}    | @{fg highlight}Yes@{fg text} | @{fg highlight}Yes@{fg text} | Melody samples
------------------------------+-----+-----+--------------------------------
@{fg highlight}The sample playthrough method@{fg text} | @{fg highlight}Yes@{fg text} | @{fg highlight}Yes@{fg text} | Melody samples
------------------------------+-----+-----+--------------------------------
@{fg highlight}The sample-offset method@{fg text}      | No  | @{fg highlight}Yes@{fg text} | Melody samples
------------------------------+-----+-----+--------------------------------

And that finally brings me to the end of my noise-reduction exploration 
adventure. It's been fun and enlightning to discover these techniques, and 
I'm personally looking forward to create some cleaner-sounding MODs in the 
future. I hope it has been somewhat interesting to other MOD musicians out 
there as well.

@endnode

@node digitalwintercard "Creative Graphics: Digital Winter Car"
@toc guides
=============================================================================
@{b}Creative Graphics: Digital Winter Card@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

By the time you are reading this issue the winter seasonal holidays should 
have started already. In issue 2.11 and 2.12 we covered some of the basics 
of ImageFX, in particular creating a digital summer post card. In that 
tutorial we worked with pasting and cutting images over another image. In 
this issue I thought it would be fun to do a winter version of the digital 
post card. So get out your digital camera, ImageFX 4.5, Brilliance/DPaint 
and lets get started.

@{b}Tis the season to be snowy!@{ub}

To begin with find a photo or take a photo with your digital camera or 
smartphone that you would like to be the main background image. Once you 
have the image ready, bring it into the Amiga either via e-mail, CF card or 
if you have a V4, then ApolloExplorer. For this project I e-mailed a photo 
from my wife's iPhone X. Once the photo had been downloaded the photo I was 
able to load it into ImageFX 4.5, it does take a while to load so if you are 
using a slower machine be ready to make a cup of tea while it loads. Even 
with my TF1260 equipped A1200 it took over a minute to load the file.

Once the file has loaded you will have a very large file beyond the standard 
Amiga resolutions, so we will need to scale it downto something more 
manageable by the Amiga. This Xmas card will be viewed on the Amiga so let's 
use PAL Hires (720 x 566). My imported photo is 4,032 x 3,024, I used the 
'Size' button which brought up a requestor, before doing any scaling make 
sure you have changed 'Aspect:' to 'Locked to Image's Aspect'. Since I want 
to have an image size of 720 x 566, I will not be able to fully reduce the 
size, I will need to crop the image afterwards. On the right of 'Width:' and 
'Height:' you will a slider bar and two buttons a [ ÷ and x ] , you can 
click on either the 'Width' or 'Height' [ ÷ and x ] buttons since the image 
aspect has been locked. I used the [ ÷ ] to reduce the image until I have an 
image size of 1008 x 756, again unless you are on a fast Amiga it will take 
time to scale the image.

Once finished you should still have the 'Size' window, find the 'Crop' 
button and click on it. Locate the 'Size:' boxes and enter in our desired 
image size of 720 x 566. Make sure to press the Return or Enter key each 
time, otherwise the changes will not be accepted. After pressing the 
Return/Enter keys you will see a frame box appear, click in the middle to 
move it to your position of your liking. 

If at this point you feel that the image is still too large, cancel the 
'Crop' window and go back to 'Size' window and then to 'Scale' and reduce 
the image more. Instead of using the [ ÷ and x ] buttons enter in the values 
via the 'Size:' boxes.

Okay, back to cropping your image, so you have the frame box where you want, 
all you need to do next is click on 'Crop' and you are half way there. At 
this point you will want to save your image. Find 'Save' on the bottom right 
of the menu bar and choose ILBM (IFF) from the list on the right, and click 
on 'Save As' save the file name with any name you like.

@{b}It's snowing!@{ub}

For our next part we will go back to True Brilliance, for this tutorial I 
used Brilliance but the techniques can be used in DPaint as well. Once you 
have loaded up True Brilliance we need to set the image size or in 
Brilliance, the 'Page Size'. This is done by going to the 'Screen Settings' 
button, and selecting a resolution of PAL HiRes Laced and selecting the 
button 'Max' which uses the Overscan and gives you a nice large resolution 
of 720 x 566.

Now we can make our snow, keeping the background black, select white and go 
to 'Pen Tip', find the tip from the third from the left and paste down 
several dots around the screen. We don't want too many otherwise we will 
hide the picture behind the snow. After then choose the second from the left 
and the first from the left, putting down dots randomly to look like snow.

When you are finished we need to smooth out the snow, select the 'Rectangle' 
tool and then  right click on 'Draw Mode' , find and select 'Smooth'. Now, 
draw a rectangle covering the entire screen. It will take a while to 
complete the process but once it is finished you will have an image with 
nicely anti-aliased snow. Save the image in the same directory as your photo 
that was processed in ImageFX.

@{b}Back to ImageFX!@{ub}

First you need to load your edited photo into ImageFX, once you have it 
displayed on screen we need to sart using ImageFX's layers. This is done by 
clicking on the 'Layer Manager' button found on the left side of the R G B 
buttons. The 'Layer Manager' window will appear, locate the down arrow on 
the top right, left click hold and select 'New Layer from Buffer', this will 
make your photo the 'Background' layer. Click on the eyes to hide the layer.

Click on the down arrow again and select 'Load Layer', locate your snow 
image that you made in Brilliance/DPaint and click on 'OK'. The MAIN window 
should turn black with only the white snow flakes showing. We will need to 
blend the layers and this is accomplished by left click hold on the 'Mode:' 
button, make sure you click on the text and not the arrow to show the drop 
down menu. Select 'Lighten' and lo and behold the black part of the image 
will disappear leaving only the snow. If the snow is too bright or harsh you 
can adjust the transparency with the 'Blend %:' slider.

At this point you might want to save your image, be aware when you do, that 
you will need to flatten the image, which can be done via the down arrow 
button. 

Now you have your photo with snow added, it is time to add some simple text. 
While you could use the text feature in ImageFX I find that you get better 
results by putting in a little more effort. For our text we have two options 
we can use FinalWriter/Wordworth or DrawStudio. In my case I used DrawStudio 
to create the text, I then saved the text document out as a bitmap and 
imported it into ImageFX. Using the same techniques for cropping, crop the 
image until you have almost no space around the edges.

We plan to create a 3D model to render in LightWave, so if you have followed 
the previous tutorials you will be familiar with this. We need to flip the 
colours, so click the 'Color' button and then click on 'Negative', this will 
turn the black text to white and the background to black. Save out the image 
as an IFF (ILBM).

@{b}Extrude!@{ub}

Next we will need to create a 3D object out of the bitmap, go to PixelPro 
and load your image. Click on 'Extrude' and use a value of '20', it will 
take time on machines that do not have an 060/080/PiStorm so if you have an 
old 030 then prepare to make lunch while the Amiga is working. Once it is 
done you can click on 'Save' and choose 'LightWave' object. 

Now we need to use LightWave, load up the LightWave programme and not the 
modeler. Once you in LightWave, go to the 'Objects' button and load the text 
object we made in PixelPro. Once the object has loaded, adjust it so that it 
is at an angle to enhance the 3D effect.

After adjusting the placement of your object and camera remember to click on
'Current Frame' where it the number '0' is, click once there and then press 
the 'Enter' key. If you do not do this it not keep the camera and object 
co-ordinates when you render. You do not have to do anything regarding the 
background however it would be wise to change the surface of your object, 
you can change the surface colour or add a texture from the 'Surfaces' 
panel.

Make your sure camera, object and light are placed just where you want them, 
do a test render of your scene. If you are happy then click on 'Record' and 
select 'Save RGB Images' to save your image. Once it is finished rendering 
close LightWave and back to ImageFX again.

@{b}ImageFX ... Again!@{ub}

Now we have all our parts again, if you saved your image then you just need 
to load it, if you did not save the image the first time round then you need 
to repeat the processes above in ImageFX. With the rendered text, you just 
need to follow the same process of loading the image as a layer and then 
changing 'Mode' to 'Lighten'. You should now have three layers with the 
background photo, snow on top and the text on the final top layer. All you 
need to do is render the image as an IFF 24Bit, 256 or lower and then e-mail 
it to your friends, family or even post it on the WhatIFF? forum. 

Happy Holidays from me, thank you for having followed this series over the 
years and and I look forward to doing more in 2025!

@endnode

@node amigaos3.2menutools "New Users 101: Amiga OS3.2 - MenuTools"
@toc guides
=============================================================================
@{b}New Users 101: Amiga OS3.2 - MenuTools@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

Amiga OS3.2 has brought a slew of new features to the Amiga, and one of 
those is MenuTools which can be found in the WBStartup directory. Clicking on
the Workbench menu bar and the final item you will see "Tools", by default
it lists: ResetWB, Auto-Arrange Icons and Help. However there is a relatively
easy way to add your own items to the menu, I say relatively as it does
require use of the Shell and the commands are not that straight forward.

To begin with, you need to open a Shell window and type "ed" followed by a
space, then located the MenuTools icon in the WBStartup drawer and drag it
into the Shell window. Some more text will appear, press Enter to open the
file.

You want to find the two lines that start with MENU ADD, they should look 
like the following:

MENU ADD NAME MenuSeparator1 TITLE '"~"' CMD ""
MENU ADD NAME MenuHelp TITLE '"Help"' CMD "'address command ''Help'''"

As you can see it is relatively straight forward, but to help you understand
it better we will work through an easy example. For this scenario we will
add the e-mailer YAM to the menu.

To begin with let{s add: MENU ADD NAME MenuYAM TITLE '"YAM"'

This first part will add a name/item to the menu, next we add the command to
menu bar. That will look like this:

CMD "'address command ''Work:YAM/YAM'''"

When finished the entire line should look like this:

MENU ADD NAME MenuYAM TITLE '"YAM"'CMD "'address command ''Work:YAM/YAM'''"

Interestingly if you want to add system commands it is a bit easier, as an
example if you wanted to add the Shell to the menu you need to add the
following:

MENU ADD NAME MenuShell TITLE '"Shell"' CMD "'address command ''newshell'''"

If you put in Workbench:System/Shell or Shell into the "'address command ''
section you will encounter an error upon loading Shell from the menu.

The newshell command works without issue, looking into this more I found I
was even able to call Preferences items such as ScreenMode by simply using
ScreenMode as the command.

MENU ADD NAME MenuInput TITLE '"Input"' CMD "'address command ''Input'''"  


@endnode

@node amigaos3.2install "New Users 101: Various Ways to Install Amiga OS3.2"
@toc guides
=============================================================================
@{b}New Users 101: Various Ways to Install Amiga OS3.2@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

For many this guide may seem easy hat but of recent I have seen increasing
posts on forums asking how to install Amiga OS 3.2 on their real Amigas. 
Those of who are coming back to the Amiga after a while it can seem a little
daunting at first. With this guide I will take you through the steps 
necessary to get a basic install of Amiga OS on your real Amiga. Where 
necessary the guide will mention if extra hardware is needed and where to 
obtain it. Thanks must go to 'amienslaver' over at AmiBay who helped me
with a few questions I had when writing this article.

So you got your new Amiga OS package with the CD-Rom and probably you notice
right away that there are no floppy disks, welcome to the Amiga in the 
2020s! Over the last few years the ADF format has become the standard way to
distribute Amiga software but if you have an Amiga with only a floppy drive
this can be a bit tricky. So what options are available to you? 

@{b}1. Easiest but time consuming: GOTEK@{ub}

The easiest way regardless of your Amiga would be to invest in an external 
or internal GOTEK drive. It is a simple task of copying the ADF files over 
to an USB stick/thumb drive and then accessing the disks via the GOTEK. You 
are able to boot from the GOTEK and install from multiple disks using the 
disk selector.

If you have an internal hard disk or compact flash disk, then you can 
install just like in the 90s using the GOTEK instead of floppy disks. If you 
have an A500 then the GOTEK is your easiest and best option.

@{b}2. PCMCIA CF Transfer@{ub}

If you have an A600 or A1200 then things will be easier for you since you 
can use the PCMCIA slot to transfer the ADF files to a floppy disk. Saying 
that it is also possible to 'soft' boot the ADF files depending on the 
software you are using. AmigaKit sells a useful floppy disk that has the 
compact flash drivers already installed, boot from their disk and insert 
your CF card to access to the files. They also include an ADF writer if you 
wish to copy the ADF files to a real floppy disk. Once you have made your 
original Amiga OS 3.2 install disks reboot with the Install disk and go 
through the usual motions to install Workbench.

@{b}3. Emulation and a real Amiga@{ub}

The third option I use quite often and this is using a combination of the 
PCMCIA CF card transfer, emulation and ClassicWB.  To begin with I create a 
blank HDF in UAE, this can be done on either a PC or Windows machine. Then 
mount the install ADF and the CD-ROM in UAE. This will boot from the install 
disk and allow you to use the data on the CD-ROM saving you the trouble of 
swapping many disks. Once the installer disk has loaded, format the HDF 
file, calling it System or Workbench and then run the installer from the ADF 
remembering to activate the CD-ROM.

Install as normal, once it is finished you can go back to UAE.

Now this is a bit unusual what we will do next but for those who are coming 
to the Amiga after being away a while or who are new, sometimes you don't 
want to spend lots of time installing all the necessary bits and pieces. To 
speed everything up download and install ClassicWB, you can find out how to 
install it from the website it is very easy.

Okay once you have ClassicWB setup, set the ClassicWB as your main bootdisk 
and the recently installed OS3.2 HDF as a second drive. Finally, add a third 
drive and set it the Desktop directory. Once you are in ClassicWB go to 
DOPUS, find the OS3.2 drive, select it all and click on ZIP, name the file:

system.zip - this is very imporant.

Make a cup of tea while DOPUS does it thing, once it has finshed look for 
the System.zip file and copy it to the Desktop directory. From there copy 
the file to your CF card. The reason for doing this all is that ClassicWB 
comes with a handy installer compressor on an ADF, if you copy the 
System.zip to your Amiga internal hard disk and then run the installer from 
ClassicWB it will unpack your files onto the Amiga hard drive. 

Why do it this way?

It is safer and faster to setup Workbench in UAE first, test everything and 
download files, install extras first and then copy the entire install over 
to the Amiga.

@{b}4. Flash an Image of an HDF@{ub}

As I use a Mac this might vary slightly from Windows users but the general
should be the same. In part 3 I mentioned about creating an HDF and then 
installing Workbench 3.2 in UAE. In this case you might want to have a disk
with partitions so you will need to go to the HDF Disk Image Creator that
can be found from the dropdown menu on the top left side of FS-UAE, the 
button is blue with an Amiga tick in the centre. Select HDF Creator and
choose the second option:

	HDF - Partitionable Hard Drive Image (RDB) 

Once the disk image has been made you can boot into Workbench 3.2 from the
HDSetup3.2.adf disk since you will want to partition your drive. Once the
disk has loaded go to HDToolBox, do not double click it but select the
icon and then go to Info from the menu bar. Go to the Icon tab and find
tooltypes located below, search for SCSI_DEVICE_NAME=scsi.device

You will need to change this to SCSI_DEVICE_NAME=uaehf.device

If you do not change this HDToolBox will not be able to see the hard disk
file that you created in FS-UAE. From here you can partition your disk
just like you would on a real Amiga and install Amiga OS3.2.

Once you have made sure the install is booting correctly and have installed
your preferred programs and utilities, you can flash the disk image
to a CF card using `balenaEtcher`, or 'PiImager' then you can just pop the 
CF card back into your real Amiga. The HDF file might not show up initially
when using 'balenaEtcher' or 'PiImager', so when in the file requestor
make sure to have 'All Files' option selected. Or you could add .iso to the 
HDF file name.

----->

So there you have four ways to install AmigaOS 3.2, while this is probably
old hat to many Amiga users I hope those who are new to the Amiga or are
returning after being away for a while will find this guide useful.

@endnode

@node lightwave101 " LightWave 101: Cleaning Up Objects"
@toc guides
=============================================================================
@{b} LightWave 101: Cleaning Up Objects@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

In past issues we have done a few LightWave tutorials, from building a
boing ball to creating 3D text. One area however that we did not cover is
cleaning up your objects. Usually these errors can only be seen when you
render and object but there are a few steps that you can take before
rending to help reduce errors. These tips I have collected from various
articles in Amiga World, Amazing Computing, LightWave Magazine and
LightWave books that I have kept from my youth. During my high school,
university and early work days I still worked on an Amiga with LightWave
and these sources proved inavaluable in the days before mass internet
availability.

Let's get started then ...

@{b}Merge Points@{ub}

This is the first task you should always do after you have finished
modelling, it is very simple but effective. Found with the @{b}Tools@{ub}
menu Merge Points deals with one and two point polygons, it also inform you
of multiple polygons that share the same space. Merge Points can get rid of
polygons with more than two points where  multiple vertices share the same
space.

Selecting @{b}Merge@{ub} or pressing 'm' will bring up a requestor with
three options. Automatic, Fractional and Absolute. In general you will want
to use Automatic, as it will only merge points that share the same space.
Absolute will merge points in a user defined distance, make sure that you
merge points in the same layer as it will not work on separate layers.

@{b}One-Point Polygons@{ub}
As it sounds, one-point polygons render as dots, great if you are making a
starfield as we did in issue 1.08. Otherwise they can be a mistake, but fear 
not as there is an easy way to find one-point polygons. Find the @{b}Select
Polygon@{ub} button on the lower left of the screen, a window will pop up,
press the 'w' key to bring up the Polygon Statistics window. The window will
show the details of 1-4+ vertex polygons for the current modeler layer.

You can select polygons based on the amount of vertices or surface names.
Pressing the + key will select and the - key will deselect selected
polygons.

When you have your unwanted one-point polygons selected you can click on
`Cut` to remove them from your object.

@{b}Two-Point Polygons@{ub}

When you see unwanted lines cutting through your or on top of your object
this is most likely caused by two point polygons. We will use the same
technique as one point polygons to fix this issue. Select all polygons
with two vertices from in the Polygon Statistics window, the you can
cut the polygon to remove it from the object.

@{b}Flipped Polygons@{ub}

This is a common problem, where the surface of the polygon is facing the
wrong way, hence when the camera is looking at the object it will render
the incorrect surface. The fastest way to fix this issue is to either 
select the flipped polygon and click on the 'Flip' key, which is found under
the 'Polygon' menu or press the 'F' key. Another option is to use the 
'Align' button, but for this to work you will need to do a 'Merge' points
operation first.

@{b}Double Polygons@{ub}

When two polygons are sharing the same points in the same space this is
usually referred to as double polygons which can result in rendering
errors. We can fix this by using 'Unify' which can be found under the
'Polygon' menu.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

I hope these quick tips will be of use to you, prior to moving to Japan I
was working for a company that had asked me to create an animation of
their logo. The tips that have been described above helped me a lot
when I ran into issues with my objects especially when it came to the
animation aspect.

@endnode

