@node thinkingabout "Thinking about the past, future and the Amiga."
@toc articles
=============================================================================
@{b}@{ub}Thinking about the past, future ... - by: @{"Ivan Sorensen" link ivansorensen}
=============================================================================

@{b}Thinking about the past, thinking about the future, thinking about the Amiga@{ub} 

As I write this, the year is coming to a close and it is time to take stock 
of life. For the purposes of this magazine, that mostly means life as it 
relates to the Amiga computer.
 
Everyone comes to the Amiga community with their own goals, intentions and 
aspirations (or so we would hope). All I can outline is my own for the next 
year and it will largely be two things: First to keep using my Amiga and use 
it more.

I am not a collector. I own a single Amiga. When it dies, it will be 
replaced by a single Amiga (or perhaps one of the alternatives that now 
exist out there). The only time I had two was when I briefly ran Morph OS 
as my main machine.
 
In January, me and a friend are doing a @{b}retro month@{ub} where we will stick 
to retro video games and generally try to do as much as possible on retro 
systems. Break out Deluxe Paint again, write my tabletop RPG notes in Final 
Writer and listen to music mods in the evening, along with loads of Amiga 
gaming of course. Maybe I will even listen only to music that came out 
between 85 and 94, who knows. 

People often fret over whether the Amiga version of this game or that 
program was the best possible version, but I have always felt that was 
pointless. While I have an interest in many retro systems, my passion is 
Amiga. When I play a game what matters is if the Amiga version is fun to 
play, not whether the Super Nintendo version is 3% better because it had 
parallax scrolling.
 
Everything the Amiga can do can be done better by something else today, 
including playing the Amiga's own games, so why are we even here, if we are 
not passionate about the actual, real Amiga? 

That leads me to my second motivation, which is to shed the negativity. We 
live in difficult times and the internet is increasingly a garbage pit of 
despair. I have no intention of contributing to that any longer and as my 
retro computing time is a hobby, I want the time spent there to be fun and 
constructive. 

When you browse Amiga content on forums, you see people complaining that 
the new game someone is making (for free) does not have 64 colour graphics, 
arguing about how amazing Ranger was or whether Doom killed the Amiga. Maybe 
it is time to argue about OS4 vs Morph OS for the 200th time. Maybe it's 
time to complain about Atari ports, since we have not had enough posts about 
that in 30 years. Did you know that Amiga flopped because games came on too 
many disks? Did you know? Did you know?

An endless stream of people with an endless stream of negative comments on 
every little thing. 

And I am done with it. For next year and perhaps for the future. I will 
continue buying new hardware, new games as they get released, contribute in 
my own little way and use my Amiga to do things that make me happy. 

I hope you do too.

See you in the new year. Only Amiga makes it possible.

@endnode

@node apolloupdates "Apollo Computer V4: 2024 Update"
@toc articles
