@{b}Apollo Computer V4: 2024 Update @{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

2024 has been a busy year for the Apollo team, and there have been a lot of
updates to the hardware and software, since this is the last issue of the 
year, we will cover what has happened.

@{b}Hardware Updates@{ub}

@{u}1GB Models@{uu}

Most notably the V4 hardware has gotten updates to the memory available
boosting the standard 512MB to 1GB. The 512MB version is still available but
for another 200 EUR you can get double the memory. Why would you want this?

Gunnar explained on the Discord channel that this option is there for people
who want to develop on the V4 giving them more flexibility. With the 080 CPU 
and 1GB ram you get quite a beast of a machine. In addition the Robin Hood 
conversion to the V4 has been growing in size and according to Willem it 
looks like it might not fit into the standard 512MB V4s, so if you have a 
hankering to play Apollo Robin Hood then it is time to save up the pennies 
for a 1GB model.

There has also been the introduction of 1GB ITX Cases for the Standalone
machines as well. These add extra ports such as USB, video and audio plus
make it easier to access the internal CF disk.

@{u}100 Mhz@{uu}

While the hardware has not changed Apollo Computer are now offering models
of the V4 that have been tested at 100Mhz, you can pay an extra 59.50 EUR
for priviledge of a guaranteed 100Mhz V4. The FPGA is the same but it has
just been tested at 100Mhz.

@{b}Software/Core Updates@{ub}

@{u}Cores@{uu}

2024 brought about core number 10000 which included better compatability
with games and also improved the handling of interlaced screens. I noticed
the change when running Lightwave 3D made for a much better screen, a more
detailed list is below:

CPU Improvements

  Increased FPU precision
  Improved FINT speed

SAGA Improvements
  
  Flickerfixer added
  Improved audio
  Supports DMA burst length ofup to 256bit

Maggi Improvements

  New modes added
  Z-buffer GL modes added
  Supports a range of 3 pixel screen output formats
  (16/24/32-Bit)
  Supports cookie cutting texturing

Apollo OS Improvements

  Switch between PAL and chunky screens
  Fixed buttons in requestors
  Removal of harmless ghost sprite
  Border blanking fix

General Improvements

  Support for longer IDE cables
  Several compatability and game fixes

2024/2025 - Core Update 10500

-Improved built-in de-interlacer
-Support for SuperHires HAM screens
-Grey scale DIGITAL-VIDEO display in Legacy CRT (2Mb) mode
-Floppy read/write support in Full SAGA (6Mb) mode
-New ApolloBootMenu on Power-On (HELP key)
-Built in FAST and CHIP Memory test
-Support for two Kickstart ROMs
-Load KickStart ROM from Motherboard
-Load Backup Kickstart ROM from Core
-Animated Bootpicture on Power-On (customizable in the future!)
-Copper expanded to use up to 2Gb of memory
-HRTMon Debugger
-Improved SD Card signal logic
-Improved CPU performance
-Improved FPU performance
-Fixed an obscure bug in BlitBusy
-Improved OS Memory detection (Force unused memory to $FF)
-Enable both Fast-IDE ports IceDrake / FireBird (40+44 pin)
-68080 Instruction fixes/adds/improvements
 
Improved Atari Compatibility (work in progress)
-Atari ST Hardware
-Atari Screenmodes
-Yamaha Audio Chip
-ATARI timer chips
 
Expanded ApolloShield to support 1Gb RAM
 
Maggie Fixes/Improvements
-Fixed single white pixel error
-Added Continuous span draw mode, improving speed by 15%
-Added Cubic draw mode, improving speed 35%
-Added support for texture sizes 32x32 to 1024x1024
-Added HW auto-select of best MipMap mode
-Added Maggie DMA interleave which increases speed
-Added OpenGL texture Blend modes for transparent object like water and 
 fire
 
ApolloControl 2.0
General Cleanup
Full Board Name
Serial Number
Core Version
 
ApolloMap and ApolloFlash 2.0
Moved Extended ROM content to $F0 in Core
No patching needed anymore of original Kickstart ROM
Improved support for Amiga OS 1.33 Kickstart (ApolloBoot)
Added display of board name
ApolloFlash intelligent check on correct V4 Board
 
@{i}Please note that the new 10500 Release does Require you to update the 
ApolloMap / ApolloFlash tools to version 2.0.@{ui}

@{u}Software@{uu}

In addition to the core update there has also been some work in regards to
software. Most notable are the improvements of ApolloBoot from 9.2 to 9.2
which allows ApolloBoot to work with the latest official core 10000. There
is a newer core to come out but the latest version of ApolloBoot does not
currently support it.

2024 also saw the releases of V4 supported games such as Dice Masters and
ZombieSurvivors, in addition FlashMandel VE (Vamped Edition) was released
taking advantage of the 24BIT screenmodes and faster 080.

Overall the ApolloTeam have been busy with updates and improving the V4
system. It has been a pleasure using my V4 Standalone and seeing it get
better each year. I am looking forward to what the team comes up with and
am keeping my fingers crossed for a final version of Apollo Robin Hood or
some stunning V4 demos.
  
