@node ntscsexcursions "Excursions into NTSC"
@toc articles
=============================================================================
@{b}Excursions into NTSC@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

I recently got an A1200 again after having the bright idea of reducing all 
my Amiga gear to one V4+ Standalone. While the V4SA is a great machine it 
quickly came apparent that it still has some issues and did not work very
well as sole Amiga computer. So I went on the look out for an A1200 again
and found one thanks to Netzik on Amibay, we did a swap for my V4SA and his
A1200. I had been hoping to get a PAL Amiga and Netzik had believed it was
PAL but once I had it in my hands it turned out to be an NTSC model. Well not
the end of world but it started me on a journey into exploring what options
are available to NTSC users who wish to use the PAL software, which sadly is
pretty much most Amiga sofware.

Now there is no issue when using graphics software since you are able to 
choose the screenmode at the beginning, same with most of the later 
productivity such as FinalWriter however I started to run into problems when
I booted up my favourite tracker OctaMED v4. I encountered a cropped screen
which was not ideal, as such I started to research what I could do  to 
remedy the situation.

@{b}Option 1 ...@{ub}

The most obvious option is the 'two finger salute' i.e. the early boot menu
where you can select PAL or NTSC, via the buttons or pressing the spacebar.
This is a good option but I wanted to find something a bit more permanent.

@{b}Option 2 ...@{ub}

Software is another route to go, when I asked on EAB about suggestions for
forcing the Amiga into PAL, there were a few that stood out. TUDE, ModePro, 
TINYpalntsc, bootcontrol and Degrader. While the Amiga defaulted into PAL
mode only ModePro allowed me to view OctaMED in a PAL screen mode. However
I perceive two caveats, firsty ModePro seems to work with programmes that 
leave Workbench running and secondly when I was in OctaMED and editing 
samples the line that shows at which point the sound is being played is off 
by about 1 second. This was not an issue if I used the early boot menu and 
switched to PAL.

@{b}Option 3 ...@{ub}

So, I found while the software option of ModePro worked, I was still 
interested in what else I could do. It was then that I found out about
the hardware fix, desoldering and lifting pin 41 of the Alice chip and
connecting it to +5v would force the Alice into PAL mode. In addition by
changing the 28M oscillator for a PAL one (28.37516 Mhz), NTSC have a 
(28.636360 Mhz) one. However as a few people mentioned this is only really
necessary if I am using the RF Modulator (removed in my Amiga) or the 
composite port. However I am living in Japan and having that port set
at NTSC just might prove useful.

This option seemed quite promising but since I have fingers like sausages
and the grace of sausages to go with it, I wanted to see if someone else
could do the modification for me. I contaced people local to me and others
in Europe and America. I got quotes between 45 euros to 100 euros, with the
latter being a quote from my local area, ouch! As much as I would have
liked to have this done the total cost for shipping my A1200 and the work
was a bit too much for me.

@{b}Option 4 ...@{ub}

So far I have looked a the built in early boot menu, software options and
hardware modifications. However, this next option took me totally by 
surprise due to its ease and simplicity. Another person on EAB suggested the
Kickstart PAL Patcher as an alternative to the hardware fix. It can be found
at: https://github.com/SirCathal/KickstartPalPatcher

You will need Visual Studio but this little patch will work force the Amiga
into PAL mode via the kickstart, thus negating the need for the early boot
menu, software or hardware modifications. It even works with the latest 
3.2.2 Kickstart. Of all the options this seems the best as while having the
hardware mod done, I would rather do the least amount of hardware changes
to my rather ancient Amiga. Surprisingly Amigastore.eu were able to offer
the service of burning a custom rom with the patch and the eide.device added
as well for a very reasonable price. However it seems that they were unable
to add the eide.device to kickstart rom as I am unable to boot from my TF1260
IDE port. I have contacted them to double check about it. Now my Amiga boots 
into PAL automatically removing the need for software fixes, I am even able 
to boot PAL games from the floppy disk/GOTEK/aGOEX drive.

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

I confess that I had a PAL superiority complex with my PAL Amigas before
however since obtaining an NTSC Amiga I find myself realising there is
nothing to worry about getting an NTSC Amiga. Especially with the patched
ROMs my NSTC Amiga can run all PAL software without issues. If you are an
NTSC user and looking to have this patch done then I suggest contacting
Amigastore.eu as they have great service and know their Amiga stuff.

@endnode

@node whdload "WHDLoad Goteks and Gaming"
@toc articles
=============================================================================
@{b}WHDLoad, Goteks and Amiga Retro Gaming@{ub} - by: @{"Kristian Hesketh" link kristianhesketh}
=============================================================================

@{i}What are the best options for Amiga gamers in 2024?@{ui}

Back in the mid-to-late nineties, more and more Amiga users began to
recognise the benefits of Hard Disk ownership. Once the machine was fitted
with a drive it was hard to tolerate floppy only set-ups any longer, and
the larger storage capacity offered by the disks opened new avenues of
computing fun, mostly from a serious or productivity perspective. 

Hard drives afforded only limited benefits to gamers however, as many disk
games were written to use the full memory capacity of a 1MB machine and
threw out the OS as a result, the games were often not HD installable.

As the end of century approached and Amiga users tended to have expanded
and accelerated machines, third party HD installers for many floppy games
were developed and distributed. In some cases cracked versions of games
would come with custom HD installs shared on bulletin boards and Aminet
would see patches uploaded to install genuine floppy based originals to
HD. 

@{b}WHDLoad and JST@{ub}
Over time two programs became popular to run modular 'slave-based'
installers on HD equipped Amigas, JST and WHDLoad. Provided you had some
extra RAM these were great ways to install those hardware banging games on
your Amiga hard drive. Not only did they reduce the wear and tear on the
delicate original disks but provided vastly reduced loading times, removed
disk swapping, and often came with useful extras, such as button remapping
or level skip and other trainers. Back when I had my first Amiga I
installed countless games onto HD using JST and WHDLoad. 

Today the influence of WHDLoad and it's installers on the Amiga gaming
scene is profound. If you visit ebay and search for an A1200 with HD it
will invariable come pre-populated with a WHDLoad install pack. Searching
for help forums regarding Amiga gaming and recommendations to use WHDLoad
will not be far away. The A500 mini relies heavily on the use of WHDLoad
to make it a user friendly modern experience. And in many cases,
especially for Amiga beginners, or those looking for a quick nostalgia
hit, WHDLoad is the optimum choice for Amiga gaming.

In my case though, it is not my first choice to use a WHDLoad installed
game when playing an Amiga game, and I would argue that it shouldn't be
your first choice either, if you want to sit down and truly immerse
yourself in an Amiga game. 

@{b}Challenges@{ub}
I would like to point out that this is not a criticism of the WHDLoad
program or those who dedicate their spare time writing ingenious slaves
for it. I believe the issues I am highlighting are simply a result of the
goals of the program and slaves being difficult to reliably achieve
considering the vast array of Amiga configurations and finite playtesting
and bug reporting. 

@{i}Disk Versions@{ui}
When I was using JST and WHDLoad originally 25 years ago I would have some
teething problems. Occasionally an original version of a game would not
work. In those days you would need to send a copy of the original disk
images to the slave author to take a look at and update the slave. Today
the breadth of versions for slaves I would say is huge so I consider this
problem mostly addressed and essentially a thing of the past.

@{i}Crashing & Bugs@{ui}
I think everyone who has ever used a slave based installer will have come
across instances where the game dumps you back into Workbench with a
cryptic error message or has encountered a strange bug. If you are lucky
this will happen early on after loading and so you will have not made any
substantial progress into a game. There are various reasons why this will
happen, usually due to a combination of the myriad Amiga set-ups which
exist in the wild and not available for testing with the slave author, the
game code expecting to run on a 1MB A500, copy protection not fully
patched, FPU/MMU shenanigans etc.

Fortunately, it is often possible to bypass or avoid crashes using some of
the tooltypes available in WHDLoad, e.g. NOCACHE, which are often
documented in the readme files for each WHDLoad slave. However, this is
not guaranteed, and I have progressed to new worlds or screens in the past
only to find myself confronted with a new inexplicable error. 
Of course in such a scenario the best practice is to provide a bug report
on the Mantis bugtracker, however I imagine not everyone will complete
such an activity. 

@{i}Complexity@{ui}
WHDLoad has now reached version 19 and has a vast array of configuration
options. From my perspective I think such configurability is welcome as
the complexity is as a result of the underlying nature of getting these
old games to work in an OS legal fashion (as I understand it). But it does
mean that WHDLoad is not necessarily the most straightforward way to game
once you encounter issues. In my opinion one of the keys to the Amiga's
initial success was the simplicity of shoving a game disk in the drive
and away you go. 

By way of an example I think one of the first mistakes everyone
makes with WHDLoad is due to the mechanism to write to the HD for game
saves. By default the program will only flush the savegame to HD once
you quit using the quit key, if you give a three fingered salute before
this the save is gone forever. 

@{i}Alternatives@{ui}
So what are the alternative formats for Amiga retro gaming in 2024? 

* Original Floppies
If you are in possession of original floppies then this is an option.
Naturally if you have a souped up Amiga there is every chance that it will
not boot correctly or demonstrate gfx, sfx or speed issues in game.  This
can be mitigated using Amiga Early Startup Control (both mouse buttons at
boot on KS2+) or a degrader such a Relokick 1.4a which loads a Kickstart
1.3 ROM image into memory and allows CPU Caches to be disabled. 
If the game came with manual protection then make sure to keep the book to
hand. On the positive side this more than likely means that you will not
encounter issues with unfinished cracks. On the negative side you will
need to tolerate the floppy disk accessing speed and the risk that the
magnetic media will fail. 

* Original Floppies with External Drive
If you are lucky enough to own an external drive this will make a huge
difference to multi-disk games provided they are supported. Worth
investing in if you want to use original disks.

* Original Floppies installed to HD
Any Amiga game which came on over 3 floppy disks usually allowed for Hard
Disk installation with a native installer. Some of these are quite
terrible and will force you to install to a specific HD location, but the
installed games can usually be manually moved to another folder and
rectified if you know what you are doing in AmigaDOS. I find an install to
RAM: can be a useful first step in understanding what the installer is
doing (if you have this option), but not always a guarantee. Again, some
of these native installers and games will struggle with a souped up Amiga,
but you can try booting without start-up sequence and disabling CPU Caches
or trying something like TUDE as a degrader. It is worth noting that this
is not always a better alternative to WHDLoad - a game such as Beneath a
Steel Sky has a screen which will crash on any CPU above 24-bit (030 and
above) which is captured as part of the WHDLoad readme - but in general, I
notice far fewer issues once I have the game and running.

* Cracked Floppies
All the rage during the glory years and also the initial golden emulation
period as ADF files became the standard and can be easily written to Amiga
floppy. A similar experience to Original Floppies, however I would
recommend doing some research to understand whether the cracks are known
to be 100% working before investing any time in playing. Cracked games
often come with trainers full of cheats to help you see more of the game
than you otherwise would by playing through standard play.

* Gotek
At some point in the 2010s the Gotek drive was created and began to get
popular. This is a great device to gain the benefits of floppy based
gaming without the ongoing cost of replacing aging DD floppy disks or the
reliability concerns of magnetic media.

The Flashfloppy software by Keir Fraser also supports the IPF format
(through use of HCXFE program and converting to HFE v3 file format) which
provides all the benefits of original floppy disk use. You can of course
also use cracked adf provided you are comfortable these are 100%.
You can even get external Gotek drives in this day and age, which greatly
improve the usability of a Gotek only solution. I would strongly recommend
getting a Gotek with a rotary selector and a dot matrix screen for quality
of life benefits.

@{b}My Golden Rules for WHDLoad@{ub}
WHDLoad has great utility, it's amazing to see it is continually developed
in 2024, and it is sometimes the only option to play tricky older games on
a powerful Amiga, so I would say it is an essential piece of Amiga
software. For me though, I would always suggest if playing seriously to
start with one of the alternative methods, unless there is a special
feature or specific benefit a WHDLoad slave brings, or you are just doing
some quick testing. 

I would suggest Adventure games, point and click for example, or strategy
games, are the worst fit for slave-based installers as you can invest a
large amount of time only to find a late crash and these will often come
with native HD installers. 

Even though JST may be forgotten by some users now, it still has found a
niche with KS1.3 users and on lower memory configurations. Also, CD32Load
has been developed based on it which has some unique features for CD32
users wanting HD installs. 

@{b}My set-up@{ub}
I have an Amiga 1200 TF1230/50 128MB RAM, Internal GoDrive and External
Gotek and a CF card HD. I have a massive WHDLoad installed games folder
which is great resource to have, but a separate partition for serious game
playing and a spreadsheet where I record the degrading steps needed to
play old Amiga games.

What do you think? Share your thoughts on the best formats for Amiga retro
gaming in 2024.

@{i}kristian@whatiff.info@{ui}

@endnode

@node elephantsballoon "WHDLoad Goteks and Gaming"
@toc articles
=============================================================================
@{b}Coding The Elephant's Balloon & Other ... @{ub} - by: K.P.Koljonnen
=============================================================================

Said Rob in July 2024:
"Hi, I was wanting to discuss with you making a simple musicdisk executable. 
In particular one which uses fastmem replayer, probably also using 
medplayer.library"

To which I replied:
"I might find myself suddenly bored and do a small program to open an IFF 
pic and do MED playback"

On the 27th of October there was in fact not an IFF pic viewer with MED 
playback but something more complicated. From my point of view this evolved 
into a learning exercise on how to do graphics using just system libraries, 
as this was not a very familiar territory for me.
 
As a personal challenge I wanted to keep it running on kickstart 1.3.

I started by opening a 32-color system screen and implementing an IFF 
picture display mechanism (I had some IFF handling code available from 
previous projects). I then integrated Teijo's MED playback code and added a
right click menu to control the playback. 

The menu font was changed to helvetica 9. We did not want a multi-file 
application so this was a bit tricky. Fonts usually are loaded by 
diskfont.library from SYS:Fonts. Here I embedded the font data into the 
executable and manually added it to the system font list to make it 
available for intuition menus.

A scroller was then added to the bottom of the screen. I decided to try 
a copper gradient which I had previously attempted only with a 
custom copperlist and OS disabled.
It took a while to figure out how to use CopperListInit, CBump, CWait, CMove 
and RethinkDisplay. Dragging the screen down with mouse also moves the 
copper color gradient.

It was nice to realize the system is doing the heavy lifting for you.

The main screen now has a picture. Maybe after the picture there could be a 
waveform scope display, that would go nicely with the idea of a  music disk.

Some usable scope code was naturally also available (from HippoPlayer) 
so I started integrating that. I soon realized a few issues:
- A full screen wave scope is not going to run at full frame rate (on A500).
- The display is going to be subject to tearing (ugly).
- The scroller at the bottom is going to not run smoothly anymore (ugggly) 
  and may be overwritten by the scope plotting. 

The tearing problem is handled by setting up a double buffered screen. Basic 
stuff for non-OS coding. How do you do that on a system screen? Turns out 
kickstart 3.0 and newer has specific support for this. Luckily you can also 
do that with kickstart 1.3 using ScrollVPort. The idea is to have two screen 
buffers and select the front buffer with ScrollVPort for display, leaving 
the other to be the back buffer and used for drawing. Technically what this 
does is set up the copperlist bitplane pointers which is what would have to 
be done manually if doing the hardware hacking approach.

This got rid of the tearing. Interestingly there is a large performance
difference between kickstart 1.3 and kickstart 3.0 when using ScrollVPort.
That is, kickstart 1.3 is much slower, but it works, so let's go with that.

But now a new problem is apparent: the screen title bar flickers. This is 
because only the other buffer contains the title bar graphics drawn by the 
OS. Solution: manually copy the screen decorations (with BltBitMap) so that 
both buffers have them, fixing the flicker.

The full screen multicolor waveform scope now works acceptably but the 
scroller is jerky. It should be made independent of the main display update 
cycle. How do I do a proper copper screen split with the OS?

After a while I realized I can stack independent screens on top of each 
other with a suitable y-offset. The scroller then gets its own, not very 
tall, screen with no title bar. 

This was a fascinating discovery for me.

The OS is alive so the scroller update could perhaps be a separate higher 
priorty task (ie. thread), but I went with  a vertical blanking interrupt as 
it's simpler to do (I'm lazy). The scroller must not use the blitter as the 
main display uses it and also it's generally a bad idea to do it from 
interrupts when the system is alive. By the way, there is a particularly
useful instruction available on the MC68000 for scrolling pixels, "roxl.w". 

Wave scope and the scroller are now independent and the scroller is smooth.
If you drag the main screen down the scroll screen stays in place though.
This is a weird hickup and nothing can be done for that on kick1.3. Kick 3.0 
allows chaining screens together and the issue can be solved that way.

The rest of the stuff mainly involved implementing various minor graphical 
effects, using all the available bitplanes, for example to display some 
additional graphics. There's a lot of palette transitions and cross fading 
as well, which is doable as there's plenty of colors available.

The only hardware hitting part is in Teijo's MED replay code. The 
application is not compatible with RTG displays as many effects rely on 
manipulating bitmap structures and then blitting these to screen. All 
bitplane manipulations should be done with OS functions only to be RTG 
compatible.

In general I'd say it was refreshing to do some demo-like coding using just 
the OS. It's  more straight forward as the OS handles a lot of things for 
you. No need to care about the details you need to consider when hitting the 
HW.

On the other hand, there is no fine grained control on what is actually 
happening and the performance is out of your own hands in some sense. I was 
a little bit surprised how good it was on a 68000 based Amiga, but only with 
kickstart 3.0 or newer.

On kickstart 1.3 it is not smooth, but it does work, so that's nice :-)

@endnode

