@node marcelinterview "Marcel Maci Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
=============================================================================
@{b}Interview: Marcel Maci - FlashMandel VE @{ub} by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

@{b}Hello Marcel, thank you for taking the time for this interview, can you 
start off by telling us about yourself and how you got involved with the 
Amiga?@{ub}

Thank you for having me! My name is Marcel Maci (RedBug on Discord) and I 
live in Fribourg (Switzerland). I am 51 years old and married. My parents 
bought me an Amiga 500 for Christmas 1987 (the classic setting with 1 floppy 
drive, a 1084 monitor and a 9 needle color printer). I never owned another 
Amiga after that, but when I heard about the Vampire project (and especially 
the V4 Standalone) I was totally blown away by the idea that a "new Amiga" 
was coming out more than 30 years after the demise of Commodore and 
officially "came back to it" in 2019.

@{b}1. Currently you are working on FlashMandel `Vamped Edition`, what inspired 
you to work on a new version?@{ub}

I think my first contact with Fractals was around 1992. I was very 
fascinated by those images! I was also fascinated by mathematics and (fast) 
computers, so I bought (yes, not an Amiga, but) a 486 DX2 50 Mhz (5600.- CHF 
at the time - I had worked in a super market the entire summer vacation to 
earn enough money to buy it). There was this (famous) program "Fractint" 
(for MS-DOS) which was incredibly fast and offered the possibility to 
explore a lot of different fractals. I also bought a book (Otto Peitgen, 
Hartmut Jürgens, Dietmar Saupe, "Chaos and Fractals - New Frontiers of 
Science", almost 900 pages) which explained the theory behind those 
fractals in a very understandable  way. Fortunately, I had a friend who was 
very good at programming and he helped me a  lot to learn (Turbo) Pascal, 
C(++) and - finally - Assembly. During school (and in-stead of paying 
attention to the teachers (..)). I was secretly reading "Hardware Reference 
Manuals" (which allowed us to do crazy things like switching from MS-DOS "
real mode" to "protected mode"). This allowed access the entire - and 
incredible - 16 MB of memory we had at the time. Anyway ... It was fun and 
it was the first time that I really had the ability to understand how a 
computer works in depth. After that, I literally never touched assembly 
again ... But with the Vampire all these memories came back.
 
The desire to learn "m68k assembly" (which was completely new to me) started 
with writing two tutorials (mainly about the "SAGA chipset" and 68080 FPU 
programming) and I used, again, the Mandelbrot as an example). At about the 
same time I discovered the program FlashMandel and saw that it was not only 
very well done, but also came with the source code (which, technically, 
opened the possibility to do a "Vamped Edition"). 

@{b}2. Could you tell us a bit about the history of FlashMandel and how you got
   involved with it?@{ub}

I don't know the entire story about FlashMandel, unfortunately. What I know 
is that the original program (the 68k version) was done by Dino Papararo 
(between 1996-2001). 

Dino wrote to me that he started his very first "fractal experiments" on an 
Amiga 2000 and in AmigaBASIC (but due to slow speed he then switched to C 
for the main program and assembly for the core routines). He also did a lot 
of experiments to make the program faster (the declared goal beeing to write 
the fastest fractal program on AmigaOS in a system-friendly way). Other 
people (still mentioned in the "About" requester of the "Vamped Edition" by 
the way) contributed to these experiments. Later there was also Edgar Schwan 
(who contributed to the creation of Reaction GUI). In the meantime, there 
are different versions of FlashMandel available via Aminet (like FlashMandel
WOS, FlashMandel_OS4 and FlashMandelNG) and Dino is still actively 
developping Flash-Mandel up to this day. All these "downstream versions" 
share that they start from the original m68k code. In addition to extending 
the functionality, they make specific optimizations for the platform and 
processors they run on. My idea was to do the same for the Vampire. In 
October 2023, Dino published a new version of FlashMandelNG, and this was 
finally my chance to contact him (before, I didn't have an actual email 
address) and ask him for permission. Dino was very open and helpful from 
the beginning so I could finally start to work seriously on the project.

@{b}3. What was your vision for the new version of FlashMandel when you first 
   began working on it?@{ub} 

Well, as for every fractal program it should be faster ... ! :) First of 
all, I must say that the tiling algorithm included by Dino Papararo is 
already very fast (and it is a very nice and very well done recursive 
algorithm). But I have always been a big fan of the "boundary trace" 
algorithm (which, in many cases - not always - is not only faster, but 
also fascinating to observe). Second, the program should also offer more 
fractals (like, for example, the "Burning Ship" fractal or "Buddhabrots") 
and new functionalities (for example true color screens and additional 
coloring algorithms for these). At the same time, I wanted to preserve 
backwards compatibility as much as possible. So, the "Vamped Edition" 
should still run on "classic Amigas" (and even PAL / NTSC screens, 
although I didn't have the chance to test this much).

@{b}4. What were the most significant technical challenges you faced while 
   developing the new version of FlashMandel?@{ub} 

I was very lucky to start with a very clean and well organized codebase 
that also included a working build system which helped me a lot to get 
started. Otherwise - and basically coming from my Amiga 500 and AmigaOS 
1.3 as previous experience - I think I would never have been able to do it. 
At a certain point, and as the program was growing, I noticed that the 
compiling time was getting longer and longer, so that my workflow 
("modify-recompile-test", then restart) simply didn't work anymore and I 
got really frustrated ... The problem was that the program was one big 
source file that had to be compiled in one block. The solution was, of 
course, to split it up into different "modules" that could be built 
separately (and only recompiled if necessary). Doing this was kind of a 
nightmare ... also because I had added a new functionality here and a 
new line of code there (so, not in a very organized manner). It took 
several attempts to reorganize all that, and several times I ended up with 
a codebase that simply didn't compile anymore. After this hurdle, working 
on it was a pleasure again. It only got complicated again when I prepared 
the final release: I wanted the program to be compatible with ApolloOS, but 
there were different compatibility issues. Also, some users on Discord 
reported all kinds of problems on their machines. There were also strange 
"Enforcer hits" on WinUAE. I would never have discovered and solved all 
that without the help of the community and I think it is really great and I 
am really thankful that such an "ecosystem" exists around the Vampire! 

@{b}5. Have there been any major changes or improvements in the new version that 
   users should be excited about?@{ub} 

Yes, of course - in the end this is what it is all about! ;) What I 
personally like in FMVE is the possility of comparing different algorithms 
and calculation times. For example you can go from the (really inefficient) 
brute force algorithm (which may take up to 40 seconds) to the boundary 
trace algorithm (which sometimes gives you a result in less than a second). 
Another really cool thing is the Buddhabrot. Let me put it like this: If 
the Mandelbrot is already a challenging fractal (computationally speaking) 
you are not even close to the "beast" that the Buddhabrot is ... A 
Buddhabrot calculation can literally take hours, days or weeks! Just to give 
you an idea: There is a guy named Benedikt Bitterli (you can easily find 
him and his articles online) who did some videos with animated 4K 
Buddhabrots (imagine the complexity) and he literally fried his computer 
making the calculations! During my first experiments with the Buddhabrot on 
the Vampire I typically let it run during the night. Even after 12, 14 or 24 
hours the results weren't really great. 

Reading more about possible optimizations, I finally succeeded reducing it 
down to taking minutes (for the main view, zooms take longer ... :). I think 
that this is amazing for a computer that is <100 Mhz! Other great 
improvements of FMVE are new fractals (e.g. BurningShip or Multibrots), more 
configurable parameters and truecolor screens with new algorithms for smooth 
coloring.

@{b}6. Were there any specific areas of optimization you focused on to improve 
   performance or image quality?@{ub} 

Yes. Apart from very efficient algorithms (which is always the first thing 
a programmer should start with ;) ) FMVE uses a series of technical, vampire 
specific optimizations. For example: 3-operand-instructions (fmul fp0,fp0,
fp1 instead of fmove fp0,fp1 plus fmul fp0,fp1 - to save 1 instruction). Or: 
The use of extra registers (especially extra floating point e-registers 
e0-e23). 

It also uses the fact that the Vampire can execute several instructions in 
parallel when the instructions are scheduled correctly (this way the tiling 
algorithm, for example, can actually calculate 4 Mandelbrot points in 
parallel which makes it very efficient). There are other "classic" 
optimizations that have been done (like write directly to screen buffer 
instead of using the system drawing functions).
 
These optimizations potentially interfere with "system-friendly" programming 
but I think FMVE can now very cleverly turn such optimizations on or off 
when necessary ... :)

@{b}7. Can you walk us through the development process of the new version of 
   FlashMandel?@{ub}

It was an incremental process that started in autumn 2023 and took until 
September 2024 (release version 24.9 R2). It could have taken longer of 
course, because such a program is basically "never finished" (because there 
is literally an endless number of features that could be added). I worked on 
it a bit "on and off" during this year whenever I had some free time. I had 
to interrupt that for a longer period in spring because my wife and I moved 
to the "Basse" (the old town of Fribourg) and as you can imagine, during 
that time I had "other fish to fry" (paintings and renovation works for 
example).
 
Around summer, to focus on a concrete goal and get a "release" done, I 
started separating "must have" and "nice-to-have" functionalities. During 
all this time, I quite regularly posted new versions on Discord and/or sent 
updates to Dino. Towards the end (i.e. shortly before the release) I had the 
chance to utilize some "overtime" I had accumulated at work, so that I could 
dedicate more or less an entire week to finish the program (which was very 
good and almost necessary).

@{b}8. What tools or development environments did you use to work on this 
   project?@{ub} 

The tools involved were: SAS/C (C compiler), VASM (assembler that supports 
all the new instructions for the 68080), Annotate (an open source editor 
with a customized file for syntax highlighting) and some minor tools (like 
build scripts, LHA and a samba share for backups). I must say that I am a
 big fan of native development (directly on the Vampire, because this is 
what we buy them for I think;) and - coming from Linux - I do most of the 
things on the command line. Even though, as I already said, the final goal 
was to run FlashMandel on ApolloOS (I, by the way, totally support the 
open source approach of the ApolloTeam here), I used AmigaOS (actually a 
customized Coffin) for convenience. My point here is that when I have time 
to program, I want to be able to start right away and not lose time setting 
up and configuring a system (in addition I am not really good at 
partitioning harddrives and such ... :).

@{b}9. Did you collaborate with any other developers, designers, or the Amiga 
   community during the development?@{ub} 

Yes. From time to time I sent updates to Dino (both FlashMandelNG and 
FlashMandelVE are on Github by the way). I also included one of his coloring 
algorithms (while he integrated the boundary trace algorithm into Flash-
MandelNG). Apart from that, the most important collaboration (especially for 
vampire-specific things) came from the Discord community. I didn't count all 
the intermediate versions I posted there, and many users tested them on 
their machines and gave their feedback about it. There was an incredible 
number of bugs that were discovered, reported and fixed thanks to their 
feedback!

@{b}10. How has the Amiga community responded to the new version of FlashMandel 
    so far?@{ub}

Based on the "thumbs up" and "smileys with hearts" I got on Discord 
(especially when I posted new images that, by the way, have been included in 
the final release), I'd say that the feedback was really positive! This 
being said: Fractals is kind of "nerd stuff". I don't think people come home 
from work thinking: "Oh well, tonight, I think, I am going to calculate some 
real nice fractals ... !" :). The average user is probably more interested 
in games - and that's perfectly ok!

@{b}11. What are your future plans for FlashMandel? Do you see more updates 
    coming?@{ub}

For the moment I have no future plans for FMVE (and I mean what I say:). I 
may do more work on it some time in the future, because there are some 
really nice ideas that I excluded from this release and that would be really 
nice to implement. Just to give you one example: FlashMandel could do 
"distributed computing", e.g. there would be different "nodes" in a network 
that each would calculate a part of the image (due to the fact that 
fractals, most of the time, are very easily "parallelizable"). We could then 
do a nice demo that shows "real time zoom" through different types of 
fractals at probably full resolution by using a "Vampire farm" ... ;) 

@{b}12. Is there anything you wish you had more time or resources to explore in 
    the development of FlashMandel?@{ub} 

Yes and no. I mean: Yes, it would be cool to continue work on FMVE (and have 
more time for it). But no: I don't want to spend all of my free time on 
programs like FlashMandel and fractals to be honest. Before I started to 
work on FlashMandel my goal last year was to do more to support the Apollo
Team. The point is that over the years, I have had the chance to meet 
different members of the group at events like the OufParty or Amiga38 (in 
Germany, actually the first time I went to such a big Amiga meeting). At 
one point I was asked if I wanted to participate in writing a commodity to 
enable scroll wheel support on the Vampire. I must say that it has been a 
true pleasure to work with Gunnar and other members of the Team, so I 
actually wanted to continue there. Just that FlashMandel somehow got "in 
the middle" ... But that's the reason why I said that I don't plan any other 
release for FMVE (at least not for the moment), because I really wanted to 
have time for other things!

@{b}13. What drew you to programming and development in the first place? Was it 
related to your love for the Amiga platform?@{ub}

It was not really Amiga. On the Amiga I only programmed in AmigaBASIC (which 
actually was a very nice BASIC dialect, but - of course - slow). I remember 
that on my Amiga 500 I had some floppy disks with a C compiler and even an 
assembler. I actually gave it several tries, but the thing is: If you don't 
have someone who helps you to get over the first, most difficult hurdles,
you simply are lost and quickly lose interest! For me, the "declick" in 
programming really came with the 486 DX2 50 Mhz I mentioned earlier: 
It was this friend of mine who introduced me to C, Pascal and Assembler 
(otherwise, I am quite sure, I wouldn't have gone beyond BASIC). After that, 
once you have understood how it works, you can learn (almost) any other 
programming language by yourself. Later there was Linux (which I discovered 
from 1997 on, if my memories are correct) and I must say that open source 
software is a great way to learn! At that time, the "distributions" came 
with very good manuals (in paper form!) and they explained (actually very 
complicated) stuff in a very comprehensive way. And that's how I have 
learned everything about computers ever since ... By reading manuals and 
"asking around" (and the Discord community I mentioned is very helpful and 
supportive with this). 

@{b}14. Do you have any favorite Amiga memories or experiences that have 
    influenced your work on FlashMandel?@{ub}

I have many great Amiga memories (especially games and music), but having 
been  absent from Amiga for more than ... 30 (!) years, all the knowledge 
that went into FlashMandel really is less than 5 years old.

@{b}15. What other projects or interests are you working on or passionate about 
    outside of FlashMandel?@{ub}

Well, I have my private life with my wife (we adore going to the mountains 
or travel by bike for example), the house with our garden, our cat ... It's 
also nice to go out with friends to have dinner somewhere with a good bottle 
of wine or some beers, or to go to a concert. I still love vinyl records and
metal bands, by the way, so I think I am kind of a lost soul and definitely 
stuck in the '80s ... :). I also have my everyday job that I radically 
changed at around 40 and that I simply adore (I have been working as a train 
driver for more than 12 years now and I really think that this is the best 
job I ever had in my life).

@{b}16. Thank you for your time, do you have any final words before we 
        finish?@{ub}

Thanks again for your interest and for editing a magazine like WhatIFF?. I 
think it is really important to have such a magazine and even better that it 
comes in the AmigaGuide format! :)

@endnode

@node grzegorzinterview "Grzegorz Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
=============================================================================
@{b}Interview: Grzegorz Kraszewski - Untangle @{ub} by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

@{b}1. Hello Grzegorz, thank you for agreeing to this interview, to start off 
can you tell us a little about yourself?@{ub}

Well, I'm 52 years old, married, two children. I'm an electronic engineer 
by education (got MSc in electronics). I live in Bialystok in north-east 
Poland.

My first computer was of course... Atari ;-), 65XE model namely. After two
years of using it I decided to move to the 16-bit world, and my first choice
was Atari ST. However my two schoolmates invited me to play a bit with their
computers: a 80286 PC with Hercules graphics versus Amiga 1200. After that I
had dropped the idea of buying an Atari ST, Amiga became my dream. PC was 
out of the question.

I could not afford Amiga 1200 those days, but managed to buy an Amiga 500. I 
Upgraded to an A1200 three years later.

The highest spec Amiga I've ever used was really a beast. It was Amiga 4000
with CyberStormPPC card (68060@50 + PPC604e@233, 128 MB RAM), UW-SCSI hard 
disk, Prometheus PCI bridge, Voodoo 3 graphics. Not owned by me however. 
I got it to develop and test the Prometheus bridge itself. Which stays the 
most advanced electronic design in my life.

@{b}2. You are from Poland, recently there have been many Amiga projects
originating from there, has the Amiga always been popular in Poland?@{ub}

Not from the start. Official export of Amiga (being a 16-bit computer, so 
high tech) to Poland has been prohibited by COCOM organization, to protect 
western high tech against being exported to the Soviet Union and its 
satellites. People bypassed this ban by buying Amigas in West Berlin and 
smuggling them to Poland. That is why a lot of Amiga 500 computers in Poland 
have German keyboard layout, while we used (and still use) US layout mostly.

COCOM ban has been lifted in 1988 or so, but still Poland has been a poor
country and Amiga was very expensive. I could afford my first Amiga, a 
second hand A500, in 1994 after working the whole summer holidays as a 
construction worker. In spite of Commodore bankruptcy Amiga was very popular 
in Poland until about 1997, then young people started to switch to PC for 
better games.

After 2000, similarly to the rest of the world, only diehards stayed with 
Amiga. Polish Amiga community was relatively large, well organized and very 
social. The internet helped to keep it alive (IRC channels, websites). One 
of Amiga portals, ppa.pl, has been founded in 2001 and is still the central 
point for the community.

@{b}3. What attracted you to the Amiga and what drives you to create software 
for a soon to be 40 year old computer?@{ub}

The answer is not very original: graphics and sound capabilities. When I 
brought my newly bought Amiga 500 home, the first program I have loaded (and 
spent the whole night with it, until 4:00 AM) was ProTracker. I had plans to 
became a demoscene musican and composed a few modules. But soon programming 
took over and I started to discover the operating system, which later 
fascinated me.

In my opinion AmigaOS (especially in 3.x version) is at the same time
sophisticated enough to write useful software, yet simple enough to have a 
good understanding of it and all its components. Current mainstream opera-
ting systems start to be victims of their own complexity.

@{b}4. In September of this year, you released Untangle, can you explain a bit 
about it?@{ub}

Untangle is a simple, yet addictive logic puzzle. It is not my original idea 
of course, similar games exist on all the popular operating systems. The 
puzzle consists of a set of dots connected by lines. Dots can be dragged 
with mouse. At the start of each level many lines intersects. The goal of 
the game is to move dots to eliminate all the intersections of lines. Each 
next level has more dots and more lines.

@{b}5. Have you developed other Amiga games or software prior to Untangle?@{ub}

A lot. My first Amiga program has been written in 1995, as far as I 
remember. Unfortunately neither executable file nor source code have been 
preserved. It was a tool for calculating "wormholes" in the Frontier game. 
Then I have released a few small utilities as a member of BlaBla group. The 
group was unusual on the Amiga scene, as it only released system friendly 
utilities and tools, no games or scene demos. We had an internal bulletin in 
AmigaGuide, in which we tested and revieved each other programs and 
published articles on Amiga OS programming.

In 2003 I went the MorphOS way and joined the MorphOS Team. My main
contribution to MorphOS is Reggae - multimedia processing system, which can
be described as "next gen datatypes". I also have written multiple small 
utilities, many of them using Reggae, but not all of them.

While still in MorphOS Team (I left in 2015) I have been contracted to write
DigiBooster 3 - a multichannel music tracker. Then I had a few years of 
pause in writing Amiga software, and have started (in the year 2017) 
RastPort, an one-man business, which produces hardware accessories for Amiga 
computers.

But programming is like an addiction, a good one. So I started writing 
programs for the classic Amiga again. My first release was my first Amiga 
program written in C++, MorsConv, which is a Morse code generator. The next 
one is Untangle.

@{b}6. What inspired you to create Untangle?@{ub}

I like to have a few logic games on my phone, to play while waiting for a 
bus, or when I need a short break at work. One of games I have played was 
Untangle. I liked it and realized that Amiga has enough computing power to 
handle this type of game, so probably someone has programmed it already. To 
my surprise I have found no game of this kind on Amiga. So I have written 
one. As a fan of system friendly programming I made it to run in a window 
on Workbench.

@{b}7. It is somewhat rare to see modern Amiga games that run on a Workbench
screen, why did you choose to go this route?@{ub}

With its minimalistic graphics Untangle fits the Workbench screen without
degrading user experience. It even looks better in higher resolutions, while
graphics drawing speed is not critical. Most "usual" games run in 320 x 256 
to achieve high frame rate. Untangle has been tested in highres AGA modes 
like HighGfx (1024 x 768) and Xtreme (1280 x 1024) and it still works great.

Another advantage of using the system to draw graphics is that I can support
graphics cards without writing a single line of code specific to RTG. I do 
not explicitly use Picasso96 or CyberGraphX functions and the game just 
works. Not only on classic Amiga, but also on AmigaOS 4 and MorphOS. Out of 
the box.

@{b}8. How was the game developed, did you do it on an Amiga?@{ub}

Untangle has been developed entirely on Amiga, but often on emulated one. My
workplace at home is very constrained, so I cannot keep my A1200 on the desk
permanently. This is why I often use AmiBerry on my Linux PC. Emulator speed
is another reason. My A1200 has only 68020 @ 28 MHz, GCC compiler is not 
very fast on such configuration. The third reason for using an emulator is
possibility to test programs on different configurations.

I know that most of people coding for Amiga nowadays use cross-compilers and
modern editors like VSCode. I prefer to use native Amiga tools (my choice
is GCC 2.95.3 compiler and Redit 2.0 editor).

@{b}9. What difficulties/hurdles did you have when creating the game?@{ub}

The most time consuming task was to create game levels. It may seem easy, 
there is no graphics to draw, just a few dots and lines. Hoever not every 
random set of dots and lines is solvable. They have to constitute a planar 
graph. Verifying planarity of a graph or generating graphs which are always 
planar, are not trivial tasks, and a few PhD dissertations have been written 
on the subject.

Another difficult thing was optimization of algorithm, which detects level
completion. One has to count all the intersections of lines. If there is
none, the level is solved. The test has to be done after each move. A single 
test for a pair of lines requires 8 multiplications and some additions. 
Sounds easy, but if there are 100 lines in a level, full test takes 80 000 
multiplications. At the first glance.

A simple observation that if some line A intersects with line B, it also 
means that B intersects with A, halves the amount of computations. Another 
obvious thing is to skip the test for a line intersecting with itself. 
However the major trick is to calculate the full intersection matrix once, 
after loading the level. Then, after each move, only lines that have been 
moved are tested and the matrix is updated. 

@{b}10. The community reaction has been very positive, are there any plans for
updates or changes to the game?@{ub}

An obvious update is to add more levels. Localization of the game (using 
the system 'locale.library') is planned. I also think about adding some 
short animated effect between levels.

@{b}11. Beyond Untangle, do you have plans for other projects or games for
the Amiga?@{ub}

Sure I do. I have a working engine for Unicode bitmap fonts and I want to 
write a text editor using it and working in Unicode. I have also invented a 
new programming language for Amiga, but I'm afraid I will never complete it.
It is also possible that I will design some new hardware products for 
RastPort.

@{b}12. Since we are getting close to the end of the year, what things in the
Amiga scene have you enjoyed in 2024 and what are you looking forward to
in 2025?@{ub}

For me the most interesting thing in the Amiga scene is the process of
development of AmigaOS 3.2 system. I hope it will be continued in 2025 and 
we will see 3.3 release.

@{b}Thank you for taking the time to answer my questions and for creating
such an enjoyable game.@{ub}

@endnode

@node krzysztofinterview "Krzysztof Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
=============================================================================
@{b}Interview: Krzysztof Donat - GoVD @{ub} by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

@{b}1. Hello Krzysztof, thank you for taking the time for this 
interview, to start with can you tell us a little about yourself?@{ub}

My name is Krzysztof (Chris), Im 43 years old, and I live in Poland. Im a 
software engineer by profession, and my entire career20 years nowhas 
revolved around designing, developing, and maintaining applications. I 
currently work in IT for one of Polands telecom companies. Im also a 
husband, a father to a teenage son, and I have a cat :) In my free time, I 
like rewatching The Office, cycling, and waiting for the Polish national 
football team to win the World Cup (and yes, I know it`ll be a long wait..). 

And of course, I also create software for the Amiga!

@{b}2. How did you get started with the Amiga?@{ub}

My journey with the Amiga started relatively late, around 1995. By that time 
,Commodore had long gone bankrupt, and people were starting to move away 
from the platform. Thats when I got my first computer, my dream Amiga, well, 
almost! I had been dreaming of an A1200, but I received an A600 instead. I 
immediately installed a hard drive, and for a long time, it was my only 
Amiga. After a brief period of playing every game I could get my hands on, I 
ordered shareware disks from the Polish edition of Amiga Magazine, which 
included AsmONE and AmigaE. The Amiga taught me how to program, and I wrote 
tons of different programssome better, some worse. Unfortunately, none of 
them have survived from that time. But I still have my first Amiga, and it 
remains my favorite in my collection!

@{b}3. Prior to programming on the Amiga did you work on other 
computers?@{ub}

As I mentioned earlier, the Amiga was my first computer, and its where I 
learned how to program. It wasn`t an easy journeyback then, I didnt have 
access to the internet, and programming literature, especially about 68k 
assembly and my favorite language, AmigaE, was hard to come by in Poland. 
After some time, I also picked up C, which I also learned on the Amiga.

@{b}4. Recently you released GoVD, can you explain what it is and what it 
does?@{ub}

GoVD is an application that introduces a feature well-known from other 
systems to AmigaOS: virtual desktops. Virtual desktops are different from 
the familiar draggable screens of the Amiga, and they certainly dont replace 
them. GoVD`s virtual screens work exclusively on the Workbench screen and 
help users better organize their workspace. You can have up to 8 different 
desktops, each with its own set of windows. No more hunting for the window 
you need buried under several others.
 
Plus, virtual screens dont require any CHIP memory at all!

@{b}5. What inspired you to create GoVD?@{ub}

That's a tough question. Whenever I feel the urge to program something for 
the Amiga, I always want it to be something new, something that hasnt been 
done before. Its a very difficult goal to achieve because sometimes it feels 
like everything is already on Aminet. Usually, I come up with a brilliant 
idea, but after a few minutes of searching Aminet, I discover that someone 
else already thought of itand most often, they did it 30 years ago! 

Thats how about 90% of my 'groundbreaking' ideas end. Additionally, I dont 
have a lot of time to dedicate to the Amiga, so I tend to choose projects 
that, aside from being original, have a real chance of being finished and 
released as a quality product.

@{b}6. What software did you use to develop GoVD?@{ub}

All of the programs Ive developed in recent years have been written in 
AmigaE. At first, I used the original AmigaE 3.3 compiler, which was 
uploaded to Aminet by the creator of the language, Wouter van Oortmerssen. 
But a few years ago, an incredible developer named Darren Coles entered the 
AmigaE scene, and he has done an amazing job continuing the development of 
E by creating the E-VO compiler. Thanks to Darren, we now not only have new 
versions of the compiler but also updated system modules for OS 3.2 and the 
ReBuild program, which helps build GUIs using ReAction. Without Darren and 
his hard work, I believe GoVD wouldnt have been released in the form it 
reached the users.

@{b}7. Are there any features that you wish to add in the future?@{ub}

As for the development of GoVD, there are definitely a few ideas, most of 
which have been suggested by the users themselves. First and foremost, I 
plan to add support for switching between screens using keyboard shortcuts, 
for example, Ctrl + [screen number]. Another idea waiting to be implemented 
is the automatic hiding of the screen menu, with it reappearing when the 
user returns with the mouse cursor. I also have a few smaller improvements 
in mind, and one feature that users from around the world are asking forGoVD 
in their native languages. So, Ill likely add support for Amiga's 
localization system as well.

@{b}8. Do you have plans for other software?@{ub}

Yes, Im thinking about a few new programs for the Amiga. One idea is an 
application for managing icons, something similar to GoADF, where users 
could easily browse and edit Amiga icons. Another idea is a project I`ve 
tentatively called AmiF.lux, a program inspired by the popular f.lux 
software on other platforms. Time will tell if any of these ideas will come 
to life, or maybe Ill end up working on something completely different!

@{b}9. How has Workbench 3.2 made it easier to develop software?@{ub}

Every new feature in the system opens up new possibilities for developers. 
New functions or even a single tag can make things much easier, faster, or 
even make something possible that wasnt before. For example, the idea for 
GoVD came to me several years ago, but after a few attempts, I had to 
abandon it, I couldn`t find a way to bring the concept of virtual desktops 
to the Amiga with OS 3.1. It wasn`t until the new ShowWindow() and 
HideWindow() functions were introduced in intuition.library version 46 
(OS 3.1.4) that I was finally able to bring this idea to life.

@{b}10. You have developed other utilities for the Amiga such as GoADF! and 
RAD Manager, which one are you most proud of?@{ub}

I like all of my programs, but GoADF and GoShell are definitely my 
favorites. GoADF is a project I`ve dedicated a lot of time to, and its the 
one Im most proud of. The feedback from the community has been amazing as 
well, and I want to thank everyone for that! On the other hand, GoShell is 
the application I use most often personally. I added even the option to open 
GoShell in the background, behind other screens. Now it launches on every 
Amiga I use, giving me instant access to a full-screen Shell. I recommend 
it to everyone!

@{b}11. Thank you for your answers, before we finish do you have any final 
words or comments?@{ub}

I`d like to thank the users of my programs for all the feedback they send 
me. Its really important to me because it shows that my software is alive 
and well on Amigas around the world, and it motivates me to keep working. 
I also want to thank everyone for the support they`ve shown through PayPal.
This allows me to continue pursuing my Amiga passion, as every cent from 
donations goes right back to Amiga software publishers and hardware 
producers. And finally, a big thanks to the AmigaOS 3.x development team, 
without whose hard work GoVD wouldnt exist!

@endnode

@node carstenjensen "Carsten Jensen Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
=============================================================================
@{b}Interview: Carsten Jensen -  www.retro-commodore.eu @{ub} by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

@{b}1. Carsten, thank you for taking the time to join us today. Could you 
   provide a brief overview of your background and what sparked your 
   interest in the Amiga?@{ub}

Thank you Timo, pleasure to help the community and keeping our hobby alive.

I was rather late in acquiring my first computer - the Pong machine set 
aside, I got my C64 in '89.

The choice was a C64 or an Amiga 500, and I went with the C64 as most of my 
friends had a C64 giving me easier access to "borrow" software. It was only 
a few years later I got my A500. This was after having studied every 
possible pixel of the adverts on the back of some magazines and read all the 
technical specifications I could get my hands on on the Amiga 500. I could 
do look at those adverts for hours sitting on the backseat in my parents car 
driving many kilometers, you have, or should I say _had_ plenty of time 
looking at those still images, imagining how it would be like to own such a 
magnificent piece of electronics.

The youth now a days don't know what we're talking about. 

I still remember the advert, showcasing a blue pillow on top and an A500 
below, with each a pricetag on them. 

And the line: Dreams are for free, stop dreaming, Amiga 500 ca. 5000,- 
(Danish Crowns)

As we know, the Amiga was superior to the C64, but I ended up in having both 
setup ready to use. I used the Amiga for games and demos and many hours were 
spent here, I had a 16" TV with scart, but only mono loudspeaker. The 
picture was nice crisp using the scart cable - I did have a TV tuner in the 
beginning, it was cheaper than a scart cable.

With the C64 I was somewhat involved in the scene as a swapper, made some 
graphics and discmag editor, nothing really to talk about, but it was great 
fun.

@{b}2. What ignited your passion for the Amiga platform and prompted you to 
   delve deeper into its world?@{ub}

For years the word Amiga was all around, as kids we saw the adverts, we 
watched the marvelous monster through large store windows. So even before 
we could even touch it, we already knew what it could do. 

Finally getting my hands on one, this one was a late model, with kickstart 
1.3, green power led and yellow drive access led, and not to forget a 
switchmode power supple which weighed nothing compared to the older model, I 
had the oppertunity to see what it could do, with friends whom also got 
their A500 around the same time as me, we had somewhat good access to test 
the game of x-copy and what it could do, filling out those boxes with all 
green zeroes, who needs tetris?

Watching demos was a mixed experience.. once you've watched the first demo 
with vector boxes spinning around, and starry background, some parts looked 
like cracktros, kinda old news. After a while (might be just a short time 
and the amount of demos/parts might be very few - my memory is a little 
fuzzy) really cool demo's were received, watched, enjoyed, and rewatched. 

I still enjoy watching them to this day. Some I think are worth mentioning 
are Kefrens - Desert Dream, Spaceballs - State of the art, Budbrain - 
Megademo(s), Phenomena - Enigma, Crionics & The Silents - Hardwired. Just 
because I think they are very good entertainment visual and audiowise.

@{b}3. Your website, www.retro-commodore.eu, stands as a significant resource 
   for enthusiasts. Can you share the inspiration behind its creation and 
   its primary objectives?@{ub}

I guess it started way back to my C64 days, before I got my Amiga. There 
were some really nice RPG games, the SSI gold box series, and Dragon Wars. 
To be able to play these games you needed the manuals, as there are 
references in the games to the manuals. Not having these manuals made the 
games very hard to complete.

I never did manage to complete Dragon Wars, though I have both the Amiga 
and C64 versions on the shelf now. One of these days, I'll find some time to 
play and complete them.. I hope. Anyway, through time I wanted to complete
playing the goldbox series on pc rather than C64/Amiga, and stumbled upon 
scans of the manuals, they had shadows near the spine, some text was 
difficult to read, and in general just bad scans... back late 90's early 
2000's 300dpi was way too big, 72dpi was more than enough for the screen, 
or so they saying went.

Becoming a member of DDHF (datamuseum.dk) in around 2011 granted me later 
access to a document scanner, and with a huge manual for Red Storm Rising 
in hand, it kickstarted my career in scanning. Many hours spent scanning, 
and looking in the back mirror, waste of time. I scanned in 300dpi and in 
jpg. To my defence, I didn't know better.

Collaborating with TCD and DH from EAB through a newly started news website 
(Commodore is Awesome), I quickly learned jpg is no go, and only to use 
lossless formats.

While I only intended to scan physical game items, the danish Commodore 
community started blooming, and my local network spread. Getting feedback 
and getting access to more hardcopy I quickly expanded what I wanted to 
scan.

Basically anything that can lie on top of a scanner, as long as it says 
Commodore.

Being part of DDHF granted me access to quite some interesting and rare 
things.

@{b}4. Digitizing physical copies can pose challenges. Can you shed light on 
   the hurdles you've encountered in sourcing and converting these 
   materials?@{ub}

The hunt for a series of danish Commodore computer magazines 
(COMputer / Det Nye COMputer) has been a long travel. It has taken me years 
to collect up to where Commodore ends and the magazine is only PC. I've 
bought a lot, but also received a lot as donation as well. In my early 
scanning years, I was afraid that getting my hands on complete sets would be 
impossible. But peoples urges to come back to retro computing, or cleaning 
out their attic proved me wrong.

The worst challenge of scanning is when the item has a glued spine. You just 
can't take out the staples and run each page through a document scanner. So 
it's either to cut them up, or spend several hours scanning a single book.
It's a painful choice, in the end it comes down to rarity and accessability. 

@{b}5. When it comes to scanning, do you handle the process independently or 
   collaborate with others?@{ub}

For most, I scan myself. I have had a couple of people helping out post 
scanning. It also happens from time to time that some people want to donate, 
and through a small interview I find thay have access to a scanner, I let 
them do the scanning and send me the files.

@{b}6. Your website offers updated and colour-corrected materials. Are there 
   any plans in the pipeline for physical reprints of these resources?@{ub}

I have thought about it, and the goal with the items is to have them as 
clean as possible to print. As far as I know there are services out there 
that can do that for you. The work would be time consuming, and TBH I'd 
rather spend my time on scanning more, thus preserving.

@{b}7. With your site covering both the C64 and Amiga, which platform do you 
   find offers the richest trove of information and resources?@{ub}

Tough question, looking at the amount of books I've scanned C64 wins, but 
for manuals Amiga has a larger section. The collection of Service Manuals 
and like is much larger for Amiga than C64.

@{b}8. Navigating through the vast amount of information available can be 
   overwhelming. How do you approach curating and presenting content on your 
   platform?@{ub}

As long as it can be tied to Commodore, there is almost no filter for what 
is put online. I do even have Warranty cards scanned, though not released 
(yet). I have some papermagazines, made my children and most likely not 
distributed to more than their closest friends, which have a very low 
priority, but someone spent quite some time on them, why shouldn't they get 
the same treatment as any other magazine?

@{b}9. The CF Rescue disk for the A600 and A1200, what drove you to develop this 
   disk?@{ub}

Those disks, as far as I remember there were a few versions, were made to 
help people who'd just dug up their A1200, and wanting a way to transfer 
data to/from PC using the CF card. A typical question would be "how do I 
copy an adf file to disk, my OS3.x set has read errors". The idea was to get 
a person up running with little resources.

I did use it quite a lot in the beginning. Later I found it easier to just 
install using WinUAE. I can't remember if WinUAE could access drives 
directly at that time.

@{b}10. Currently compatible with Kickstart 3.1 systems, are there any 
    intentions to update the disk for compatibility with OS3.2?@{ub}

I haven't really thought about the disk in years, if it isn't compatible 
with OS3.2 I may take a look at it to see what can be done. If anyone has 
used it in the past 10 years, I'd be happy to know. 

@{b}11. In addition to preservation efforts, you've contributed to the DIY Open 
    Source community. Can you highlight some of the projects you've 
    initiated or released?@{ub}

Everything found on the DIY Open Source page has been initiated and 
released. Some of my older projects were made in the free version of Eagle, 
luckily KiCAD has been able to import that format for quite a while.

I've made quite a few smaller things, mostly electronics, but also a few 3D 
printable items, of the later I'm quite fond of the IEC Host case. Luigi Di 
Fraia even links to that project in thingiverse. 
                                        
@{b}12. Thank you for your answers, before we finish, is there anything you 
    would like to say or add to the interview?@{ub}

I'd like to thank everyone who has contributed/helped one way or another to 
the website. I'd also like to make a shoutout to anyone else who contributes 
to our community, spending their free time and making their products 
available to the rest of us. There are way too many names to mention, but 
if you've coded, written articles, repaired, created anything, you are one 
to mention here.

And thank you to you, the reader, without you, our community wouldn't be as 
large as it is, and it's just nice to talk to someone who doesn't look 
strangely at you and thinks.. Old computers? you're insane!

As a final note in the name of preservation, a very special thank you to 
Dave McMurtrie from the Commodore International Historical Society on 
Facebook. He has created a group with the aim of gathering and publicize 
information about Commodore.

Not only has he done so, he's managed to gather quite a few known names, 
some with a title of ex-Commodore employees.

@endnode

