himself from back in the day. In addition we have the new album from Mr Robot 
or also known as Rob O'Malley. 

As usual, we have a playlist of music for your listening pleasure with tracks 
from the following artists:

@{b}Rockbagen@{ub} by DJ METUNE
@{b}Dexroll@{ub} and @{b}Grovhakkepostej@{ub} by Sidwave
@{b}Sunshine@{ub} by MisthaLu

Some notes regading the coverdisk music album:

REQUIREMENTS:
Runs on any Amiga with an adequate amount of RAM, Amiga 1000 with only 256K 
chip should even be able to handle it as long as you have an extra 8MB of 
other RAM!

Runs better on WB3 with 020 and above, and of course enough RAM, again you 
really want an extra 8 megabytes of the stuff.

USAGE:
Really I think that operating this thing is pretty intuitive but maybe it 
might help to know the following details:

* To launch the album just double click on the icon or do your thing from 
  the command line interface.

* Hitting the space bar will start the music from the beginning of the album 
  once the title sequence is ready for it, or you could use the menu 
  instead.

* The content of the music disk can be navigated by using the right mouse 
  button and treating it as you would any other menu in any Amiga software.

* If the display does glitch out a bit when attempting to access the menu 
  which it does on rare occasions just release it and try again and you will 
  eventually be just fine.

* While you can send the music disk display to the back of the screens if 
  you wish to multitask while listening please use the iconify function 
  found in the menus.

* If the screen title reads "SOS-1" then it is not currently the active 
  screen, clicking then mouse a few times should remedy that.

* Press fire button to pretend you are loading something from cassette on 
  your commodore 64.

* And if you press enough keys at random then eventually you will surely 
  find the one that activates the (incomplete) secret sound-test section.

@endnode


